# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2013-colorado-floods
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] On July 31, 1976, heavy rainfall caused the Big Thompson River in Colorado to flood, causing at least 144 deaths, more than 250 injuries, and at least 5 others to be missing.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] The flood was caused by a stalled thunderstorm complex that produced rainfall totals of 12–14 inches (300–360 mm) near Estes Park, Colorado, including 7.5 inches (190 mm) of rain that fell in one hour.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] Cresting at 30 feet (9.1 m), the flood caused widespread damage along the river totaling almost $40 million ($150 million in 2016 USD).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] It is considered one of the deadliest floods in the state's history.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] The Big Thompson River is a tributary of the South Platte River, approximately 78 miles (126 km) long, in the U.S. state of Colorado.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] Originating in Forest Canyon in Rocky Mountain National Park, the river flows into Lake Estes in the town of Estes Park, and then through Big Thompson Canyon.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] Before the flood, 600 people lived in Big Thompson Canyon.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] In addition, between 2,500 and 3,500 people were there on July 31 to celebrate the 100th anniversary of Colorado's statehood on August 1.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] On July 31, a thunderstorm complex developed alongside the Front Range of the southern Rocky Mountains near Estes Park.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] Upper-atmospheric light winds caused the thunderstorm complex to remain stationary, which produced heavy rainfall across portions of the Big Thompson Canyon, including up to 7.5 inches (190 mm) of rain falling in one hour.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] Over four hours near Estes Park, 12–14 inches (300–360 mm) of rain fell, causing the Big Thompson River to overflow its banks and triggering a flood surge that moved along the river and into Big Thompson Canyon.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] The flood moved at an average speed of 15 miles per hour (24 km/h), and crested at 30 feet (9.1 m).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] A flash flood warning was issued at 23:00 CDT, but the timing of this was criticized because it was issued several hours after the floods began.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] Route 34 was washed out by floodwaters, sustaining significant damage as visibility on the highway dropped to zero miles.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] The flood impacted most of Cedar Cove, Drake, and Midway, and causing extensive damage to buildings in Glen Haven.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] The floods caused more than $40 million in damage in 1976 USD, equivalent to nearly $150 million in 2016 USD, including 418 homes, more than 400 vehicles, and 152 businesses being destroyed, along with a further 138 buildings damaged.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] The flood swept people as far east as Interstate 25 and areas 25 miles (40 km) away.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] Mudslides caused by heavy rainfall also closed Poudre Canyon.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] It is considered one of the deadliest floods in the history of Colorado, causing at least 144 deaths and 250 injuries, along with at least 5 missing.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] On August 1, over 800 people were evacuated from flood-impacted areas via helicopter, and were taken to a high school in Loveland, Colorado that was established as a rescue center by the American Red Cross.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] Route 34 was reopened 86 days after it was closed after portions of the highway were washed out.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] United States President Gerald Ford designated Larimer County, Colorado a disaster area.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] For 25 years after the flood, until 2001, a ceremony was held annually to remember the disaster.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] It was held at a memorial constructed off U.S.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] Route 34, several miles from Drake, containing a list of people killed during the flood; this memorial was constructed in 1978, two years after the tragedy.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] The Colorado country music singer Chuck Pyle wrote a song titled "Here Comes the Water" celebrating the actions of Colorado State Patrol Sgt.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] Willis Hugh Purdy, who raced the flood down the canyon warning residents.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/1976-big-thompson-river-flood] On October 2, 2016, an episode of Colorado Experience premiered on PBS regarding the disaster.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] In the days leading up to June 19, 2013, parts of southern and central Alberta, Canada experienced heavy rainfall that triggered catastrophic flooding described by the provincial government as the worst in Alberta's history.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Areas along the Bow, Elbow, Highwood, Red Deer, Sheep, Little Bow, and South Saskatchewan rivers and their tributaries were particularly affected.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] A total of 32 states of local emergency were declared and 28 emergency operations centres were activated as water levels rose and numerous communities were placed under evacuation orders.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Five people were confirmed dead as a direct result of the flooding and over 100,000 people were displaced throughout the region.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Some 2,200 Canadian Armed Forces (CAF) troops were deployed to help in flooded areas in addition to the Royal Canadian Mounted Police and Alberta Sheriffs Branch response.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Total damage estimates exceeded CA$5 billion and in terms of insurable damages, made the **2013 Alberta floods** the costliest disaster in Canadian history at $1.7 billion, until the occurrence of the 2016 Fort McMurray wildfire.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Receding waters gave way to a mammoth cleanup of affected areas, aided by a spontaneous volunteer campaign in which many homeowners were assisted by complete strangers.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Situated east of the Canadian Rockies, southern Alberta is a semi-arid region that does not usually receive high amounts of rainfall.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Late June 2013, a high-pressure system in northern Alberta blocked the passage to a low-pressure area to the south.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] In Canmore, a town in Alberta's Rockies, over 220 millimetres (8.7 in) fell in just 36 hours between 19 and 21 June, nearly half of the town's annual average rainfall.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] In the town of High River, rainfall amounts at one weather station recorded 325 millimetres (12.8 in) in less than 48 hours.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The rain falling on already saturated ground, coupled with the steep watershed and heavy snow loads remaining in the front ranges of the Rocky Mountains, resulted in a rapid increase in the size and flow of several rivers.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] At the peak of the flooding, the Bow and Elbow rivers were flowing through Calgary at three times their peak levels from a 2005 flood that caused CA$400 million in damages.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] MDT on June 21, the flow rate on the Bow River had reached 1,458 cubic metres (51,489 cubic ft.) per second (m3/s), five times its normal rate for this time of the year.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The Elbow and Highwood rivers reached flow rates of 544 m3/s (inside Calgary) and 734 m3/s respectively, ten times their averages for this time of year.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Government officials called the flooding the worst in Alberta's history.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] By June 24, 2013, some 2,200 Canadian Forces (CF) troops had been deployed to help in flooded areas.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Land Force Western Area brought in Coyote reconnaissance vehicles, Bison armoured vehicles, G-Wagen Jeeps, and other military vehicles.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] As communities began to flood and people became displaced, area residents mobilized to offer support and assistance to evacuees and emergency response personnel.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Some volunteers and several police officers worked up to 20 hours to help evacuation efforts despite knowing their own homes had been damaged or completely washed away.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] While coverage of the flooding spread throughout social media sites, many people and businesses also took to Facebook and Twitter to open their homes up to neighbours and strangers who did not have other places to stay or offer whatever support they could.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] In Calgary, Alberta's largest city, 26 neighbourhoods in the vicinity of the Bow and Elbow rivers were placed under a mandatory evacuation order on June 20 and 21 as the rivers spilled over their banks and flooded communities.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Affecting 75,000 people, it was the largest evacuation order in the city's history.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The city's downtown core was among the areas evacuated, as officials called for a "Neighbour Day" on June 21 and requested people to stay home, particularly the 350,000 people who work downtown.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] All schools in both the public and Catholic school districts were closed and officials urged residents to avoid unnecessary travel.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] On June 21, the Bow River had reached a record high water level of 4.09 m (13.4 ft).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] That same day, the river also reached a record high flow rate of 1,750 m3/s (62,000 cu ft/s).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Through social media, websites and blogs with a constant stream of updated contributions from the Calgary's mayor, numerous city councillors, the Calgary Police, media at all levels, and numerous Calgarians with Twitter, Flickr and Facebook accounts, the flood was extremely well-covered.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The city's largest indoor arena, the Scotiabank Saddledome, was among the facilities damaged as flood waters were reported to have filled up to the first ten rows of the lower seating bowl.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The Calgary Stampede grounds adjacent to the arena were also severely flooded, less than two weeks before the scheduled opening of the annual exhibition and rodeo, however officials vowed the event would go on.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] While emergency officials began to announce the partial lifting of some evacuation orders on June 22, Mayor Naheed Nenshi stated that it would be several days before power could be restored to the downtown core.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] City workers, assisted by Canadian Forces personnel from The Calgary Highlanders, reinforced a particularly large erosion of river bank near 8th Avenue S.E., which endangered several houses in the neighbourhood of Inglewood.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Calgary's central business district, home to many of Canada's oil company headquarters, remained inaccessible until June 26.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] A spokesman for Imperial Oil, Canada's second-largest producer and refiner, said the company was working on plans to maintain essential operations, including allowing employees to work from other locations.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Shorcan Energy Brokers, which provides live prices for many Canadian crude grades, operated out of Toronto on June 21 rather than at its usual Calgary base, although no trades in either Western Canada Select heavy blend or light synthetic crude from the oil sands were executed.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Net Energy Inc, the other main Calgary crude broker, was closed on Friday, June 21, and there was no trading.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] As the water began to recede, the city lifted evacuation orders for several communities.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] It allowed 65,000 residents to return to their homes and business on June 23 to assess for damage, but parts of 14 communities remained off-limits.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] On June 27, the Bonnybrook Bridge collapsed under the weight of a Canadian Pacific Railway freight train.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] One of the pilings of the 101-year-old rail bridge had been scoured by floodwaters on the Bow River and undermined.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] CPR officials said that because the scour occurred underwater, they had not been able to inspect it, due to river conditions.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] However, rail regulations require the ability to inspect underwater.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The buckled bridge caused the train to derail.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] As the train was carrying hazardous petrochemicals, an evacuation was ordered for the local area and regions downstream, and the train was slowly pumped dry.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] South west of Calgary, the town of High River was evacuated after flooding of the Highwood River caused water to rise over the top of vehicles in the town's main streets and necessitated the rescue of over 150 people from the rooftops of their homes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] 350 Canadian Forces personnel and 80 Royal Canadian Mounted Police officers were dispatched to assist with rescue efforts.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Members of the Alberta Sheriffs Branch were also involved in this effort.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] All 13,000 residents of High River were ordered to evacuate on June 20, and the community was largely abandoned within three days as the town suffered what local officials called "unprecedented" damage.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Among internationally recognized sites flooded in High River was the "Maggie's Diner" standing set for the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC) series *Heartland*.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] During the state of emergency in High River, the RCMP entered numerous homes in the area and seized hundreds of firearms, along with magazines and ammunition.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Although the RCMP claimed that it only seized firearms that were in plain view, many residents have complained that their firearms were well hidden, and that the RCMP caused significant damage inside homes while searching for firearms.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] There are further complaints that RCMP members subjected homes to second or even third searches in their quest for firearms in plain view.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The report concluded that, although they were not legally required to do so, communicating adequately with the public during the crisis would have prevented much confusion among partners and anger among residents.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] While residents of other communities were returning and beginning their cleanup, High River remained off limits a week after the flooding first hit.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Residents grew increasingly frustrated at what they perceived as a lack of communication from local officials, particularly the lack of a timeline to return.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Officials argued the town remained unsafe; some residences remained accessible only to divers, while E. coli had been discovered in the water.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The neighbourhood of Beechwood estates, with many luxury homes worth over a million dollars, was among those hard hit by the flood.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The Province of Alberta decided to purchase 94 homes in designated floodways (including the 32 in Beechwood), demolish most of them and return the area to its natural state as a floodplain.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Twenty-six of the houses were auctioned off for relocation.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The mountain towns of Banff and Canmore, west of Calgary, were cut off from neighbouring communities after flooding and mudslides forced the closure of the Trans-Canada Highway.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Several homes were swept away in Canmore by the rise of Cougar Creek.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] In addition to Calgary, High River and Canmore, nine other municipalities, including the City of Lethbridge; the towns of Black Diamond, Cochrane, Sundre and Turner Valley; the Municipality of Crowsnest Pass; Rocky View County; and the municipal districts of Bighorn No.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] 31, had declared states of emergency on June 20 due to flooding and some communities had evacuated residents.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Additionally, the City of Red Deer declared a state of emergency over the potential of flooding ahead of a planned release of water from the Dickson Dam into the Red Deer River.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Another dozen communities have declared a state of emergency on June 21, including several First Nation reserves; the Siksika First Nation, east of Calgary evacuated 1,000 residents.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The city of Medicine Hat, on the South Saskatchewan River downstream from the confluence of the Bow and Oldman rivers was also hit with significant flooding.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The city evacuated 10,000 residents ahead of the flooding, and facilities including the Medicine Hat Arena had begun to flood late Sunday evening, June 23.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The South Saskatchewan River peaked at 5,460m3/s, which was below earlier predictions of 6,000m3/s, but exceeded the highest recorded rate of 5,100m3/s in 1995.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Officials in the neighbouring provinces of Saskatchewan and Manitoba were bracing for potential flooding along the South Saskatchewan and Saskatchewan rivers, into which many of the affected rivers in Alberta drain.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The South Saskatchewan River reached record levels through Saskatoon, but the city did not experience significant flooding.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] 2,200 people were evacuated from the Cumberland House area in eastern Saskatchewan.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] In Manitoba, flood warnings were issued for The Pas.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Four people are confirmed to have died as direct result of the flooding.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Three people drowned in the Highwood River near High River, while an elderly woman drowned in her ground-floor apartment in Calgary's Mission neighbourhood.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Additionally, Okotoks resident Robert David Nelson was killed in an ATV rollover while checking a neighbour's home for flood damage.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] On June 24, 2013, although total damage caused by the flooding remained unknown, Alberta Premier Alison Redford, predicted it would surpass the $700 million caused by the Slave Lake fire, with much of the cost likely to be uninsurable.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The Province of Alberta estimated in August that the cost of repairing the damage would exceed $5 billion.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The Insurance Bureau of Canada stated in September that insurable losses had exceeded $1.7 billion, making it the costliest disaster in Canadian history in terms of insured damages (and without accounting for inflation), surpassing the $1.6 billion cost of the North American Ice Storm of 1998.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The bureau called the cost "staggering", and said the figure continued to rise.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The Albertan government granted the Siksika nation $93M to rebuild their communities; $10M of this grant would be used to train and upgrade the vocational skills needed to perform construction repairs.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Alberta's Minister of Municipal Affairs, Doug Griffiths, announced on June 21, 2013, that a task force that represents numerous government agencies and which earned praise for its coordination of recovery efforts following the 2011 Slave Lake wildfire would be reconvened.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] John McGowan, CEO of the Alberta Urban Municipalities Association (AUMA) described how AMSC is applying what they learned from the $700-million clean-up process following the Slave Lake fire in 2011 in their response to the flood.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] McGowan explained how the AUMA's subsidiary Alberta Municipal Services Corporation (AMSC) will provide a wide variety of services which include general insurance to the approximately 278 cities, towns and villages in Alberta affected by the flood.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Damaged public buildings, vehicles and key public infrastructure, including subsidiary damage such as, structural damage to bridges or tunnels, need to be repaired or replaced in the "biggest cleanup in provincial history".
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] "Neighbours, strangers, friends, and friends-of-friends-of-friends" helped those whose homes were damaged in Calgary's flood.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Calgary's first official call, early on the morning of June 24, for 600 volunteers resulted in an estimated 2,500 people arriving ready to work.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Calgary Emergency Management Agency director Bruce Burrell said that the City of Calgary hired contractors on larger infrastructure repairs but volunteers were needed.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Upon touring the affected areas, Alberta Premier Alison Redford who represents the Calgary-Elbow riding, promised provincial assistance in recovery efforts.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The Alberta Treasury board met early on June 24 to approve a preliminary $1 billion emergency fund for the disaster recovery program, covering immediate clean-up and repair costs.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Losses to homeowners and municipalities caused by overland flooding, not covered by regular insurance, will be covered by the province.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] While making the funding announcement Premier Redford cautioned that it could take up to ten years to fully recover from the disaster.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Harper, Redford and Calgary Mayor Naheed Nenshi took a helicopter tour of flood-damaged areas on the afternoon of June 21, and discussed the trilateral co-operation to the flood response.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] It was announced in 2013 that $2 billion was earmarked from the government's Disaster Financial Assistance Arrangements for the province and that the government was seeking a $689-million increase in funding for the program from parliament.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] A state of emergency for Siksika First Nation, east of Calgary, was declared in the evening of June 20 with approximately one thousand people evacuated from their homes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Soon after the flood started to recede, volunteer efforts began to help clean up the aftermath of the flood in Calgary.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Thousands of people descended on heavily hit areas to help neighbours and strangers clean up in the aftermath.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] Buses were organized to transport volunteers into High River, where the majority of residents were expected to require assistance.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] In November 2013, the Government of Alberta announced various projects to mitigate future flooding within Calgary and High River.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] The projects include construction of a channel to divert water around High River and a dry dam for the Elbow River west of Bragg Creek, which is upstream of Calgary.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-alberta-floods] A grant was also announced for Calgary to investigate construction of a 5 km (3.1 mi) tunnel to divert Elbow River flood waters away from neighbourhoods.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The **2013 Colorado floods** were a series of natural disasters occurring in the U.S. state of Colorado.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Starting on September 11, 2013, a slow-moving cold front stalled over Colorado, clashing with warm humid monsoonal air from the south.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] This resulted in heavy rain and catastrophic flooding along Colorado's Front Range from Colorado Springs north to Fort Collins.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The situation intensified on September 11 and 12.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Boulder County was worst hit, with 9.08 inches (231 mm) recorded September 12 and up to 18 inches (460 mm) of rain recorded by September 15, which is comparable to Boulder County's average annual precipitation (20.7 inches, 525 mm).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] This event has also been referred to as the **2013 Colorado Front Range Flood**, reflecting a more precise geographic extent in and along the Colorado Front Range mountains.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The National Weather Service's Hydrometeorological Design Studies Center stated in a document that the annual exceedance probability (AEP) for the entire rainfall event was as low as 1/1000 (0.1%) in places.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The flood waters spread across a range of almost 200 miles (320 km) from north to south, affecting 17 counties.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Governor John Hickenlooper declared a disaster emergency on September 12, 2013, in 14 counties: Adams, Arapahoe, Broomfield, Boulder, Denver, El Paso, Fremont, Jefferson, Larimer, Logan, Morgan, Pueblo, Washington and Weld.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] By September 15, federal emergency declarations covered those 14 counties as well as Clear Creek County.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The state of Colorado had been experiencing varying levels of drought prior to the week of storms starting on September 9.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Colorado has a semi-arid climate and a history of flash flooding.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The earliest recorded flood in Boulder was the great flood of 1894 which came down Boulder Canyon and flooded most of the downtown area.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The Big Thompson River begins around Estes Park in northern Colorado and flows east into Big Thompson Canyon.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] On July 31, 1976, the Big Thompson Flood of 1976 struck.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] 8 inches of rainfall fell in the first hour alone; 12 inches fell in the first three hours.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The flash flooding killed 144 people and caused $35 million worth of damage, or roughly $140 million in 2013.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Comparatively, the 2013 flood was caused by approximately 15 inches of rainfall over the span of a week, killed 8 people, and caused $2 billion in damage.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The rainfall in 2013 exceeded that of the 1976 event, but the flooding was more intense in 1976 because the rainfall that fell occurred in a much shorter time frame.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] At least eight deaths were reported by the Colorado Office of Emergency Management, with two more missing and presumed dead and hundreds remaining unaccounted for.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The town of Lyons in Boulder County was isolated by the flooding of St.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Vrain Creek, and several earth dams along the Front Range burst or were over-topped.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] On September 12, Boulder Creek was reported to have exceeded 5,000 cubic feet (140 m3) of water per second.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Boulder Creek regularly flows around 150–200 cubic feet (4.2–5.7 m3) per second.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] This caused serious damage to buildings along the creek and the creek path such as Boulder High School.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] As of late September 13, according to the Office of Emergency Management, there were 172 people unaccounted for and at least three dead in flood areas of Boulder County.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] By September 14, the death toll had reached five and more than 500 were unaccounted for, but not necessarily considered missing.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] At least 1,750 people and 300 pets have been rescued by air and ground.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Rescue efforts were hampered by continuing rain and a low cloud ceiling, which grounded National Guard helicopters September 15.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Nearly 19,000 homes were damaged, and over 1,500 were destroyed.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The Colorado Department of Transportation estimates that at least 30 state highway bridges were destroyed and an additional 20 are seriously damaged, with repairs for damaged bridges and roads expected to cost many millions of dollars.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Miles of freight and passenger rail lines were washed out or submerged, including a section servicing Amtrak's iconic *California Zephyr*.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Rainfall totals recorded by the Community Collaborative Rain, Hail and Snow Network (CoCoRaHS) from September 9–15, 2013 show significant totals in the Aurora, Boulder and Estes Park areas with several locations in the city of Boulder recording 15 to 20 inches (380 to 510 mm) of rain.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Lower-lying agricultural land in northeast Colorado was affected as flood waters surged down rivers and creeks, inundating fields and pastures.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Significant crop damage is expected from standing water that has no way to drain from fields.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Hundreds of oil and gas wells were shut down in the Denver Basin, many of which were under rushing water, and reports of broken lines and storage tanks swept away by the flood waters raised concerns of contamination.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] A spill from flood-damaged storage tanks in Milliken was reported September 18, which released 5,250 US gallons (19,900 L; 4,370 imp gal) of crude oil into the South Platte River.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The IRS announced that it would extend filing and payment deadlines for flood victims.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Structures located in high risk flood zones were soon inundated.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Sewage treatment plants affected by the flood waters released 20 million gallons of raw sewage as well as 150–270 million gallons of partially treated sewage, as estimated by the State health department.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] What resulted is higher levels of E. coli, some as high as 472–911 colonies per millimeter of water (126 colonies per millimeter of water is considered unsafe).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The Colorado Oil and Gas Conservation Commission (COGCC) reports that oil lines and containment facilities failed and leaked a total of 1,027 barrels (viz.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The COGCC is monitoring 13 substantial leaks as of October 8, 2013.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The COGCC is also monitoring 17 substantial leaks of produced water, or water that is used in the refinement of oil products and is considered waste water.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The COGCC reports that 26,385 gallons of such water has leaked into flood waters.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Over 50,000 fracking wells – a mining process utilized in the extraction of oil form the Earth – operate in the state of Colorado and 1,900 fracking wells were flooded at the peak flood levels.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] This number has since been reduced to around 1,300 wells.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Concerns have been raised about the safety of such wells in a flood situation.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The produced water from these operations sit in open pits and easily mix with flood waters and deposit toxic substances like lead or other sediments across the state.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Scientific reports that show the ecological impacts of the flooding are not readily available because this is such a recent event.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Past studies on the ecological impacts of flash flooding can give insight on what may happen.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Temporal succession has been studied in areas that experience flash flooding regularly.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] In these instances, typical biological processes characteristic to the area pre-flood resume within 2–3 weeks.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The 2013 Colorado flooding is a more complex case because of the close contact with human society.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Contamination from sewage, oil, and waste water containing toxic substances can delay natural succession processes if not alter them entirely.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] For example, waste water from flooded fracking wells could introduce levels of lead into a freshwater system, keeping a particular strain of algae from developing in usual successional form.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The hierarchy of development is now delayed or shifted into an entirely different direction.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Pollution from the floodwaters could also affect species in ways not related to succession.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] For example, animals relying on natural freshwater systems as a source for water can contract fatal illnesses as a result of the higher levels of E. coli bacteria in the water due to sewage leaks caused by the flooding.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Local media such as 9News, 7News, FOX 31 and more covered the event for its whole duration.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] President Barack Obama first declared a state of emergency for Boulder, El Paso, and Larimer counties, with an additional 12 counties added September 16: Adams, Arapahoe, Broomfield, Clear Creek, Denver, Fremont, Jefferson, Morgan, Logan, Pueblo, Washington and Weld counties.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] This authorized federal search and rescue teams, as well as supplies such as food, water, cots, generators, and emergency flood control measures.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Obama also declared a major disaster specifically for Boulder County, which provides for federal recovery assistance such as temporary housing, home repairs, and low-cost loans.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Cory Gardner (R-CO) introduced the bill To authorize the Secretary of Transportation to obligate funds for emergency relief projects arising from damage caused by severe weather events in 2013 (H.R.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] If passed, the bill would "exempt Colorado from a cap on funding, contained in Division A of Public Law 113-2 (The Disaster Relief Appropriations Act, 2013), from the Federal Aid Highways Emergency Relief program of $100 million per emergency incident." When arguing in favor of the bill, Rep.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The shutdown of the United States federal government from October 1–17, 2013 stopped federal relief aid funding going to recovery efforts in Colorado.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The state of Colorado began paying the National Guard for continuing relief efforts until the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) could reimburse the State government at the end of the shutdown.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The state hopes to be reimbursed for at least 75% of the funds.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The shutdown compromise signed on October 17, 2013, includes funding for Colorado relief efforts, specifically referencing Rep.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The cap typically set at $100 million has been raised to $450 million in light of Colorado's current conditions.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] It is not uncommon for this cap to be raised for disaster struck areas such as those states hit by Hurricane Sandy or Hurricane Katrina.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] The American Red Cross, The Salvation Army, Save the Children, the United Way, the Air Land Emergency Resource Team, Boulder Flood Relief, and Helping Pets are among the organizations accepting donations on behalf of flood victims.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Following the floods, the Colorado Department of Transportation (CDOT) initiated 200 permanent repair projects to roads.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Due to the floods being a federal disaster, CDOT paid only 20% of the $750 million expenses, with five related to Rocky Mountain National Park being entirely federally-funded.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] High traffic areas like US Highway 34 were a priority, with new infrastructure in its instance being built on dry lands.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Early projects such as these were also hastened by Governor John Hickenlooper's 60-day goal for reopening certain areas.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] In May 2022, the completion of a project on Colorado State Highway 7 in St.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/2013-colorado-floods] Vrain Canyon marked the end of flood-related repairs.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] On May 30, 1854, the Kansas–Nebraska Act created the Territory of Nebraska and Territory of Kansas, divided by the Parallel 40° North (168th Avenue in present-day Adams County).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] The future Adams County, Colorado, occupied a strip of northern Arapahoe County, Kansas Territory, immediately south of the Nebraska Territory.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] "Colonel Jack" Henderson built a ranch, trading post, and hotel on Henderson Island in the South Platte River in Arapahoe County, Kansas Territory.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Jack Henderson was the former editor and proprietor of the Leavenworth (Kansas Territory) Journal and an outspoken pro-slavery politician who had been accused of vote fraud in eastern Kansas.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Henderson sold meat and provisions to gold seekers on their way up the South Platte River Trail to the gold fields during the Pike's Peak Gold Rush.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Henderson Island was the first permanent settlement in the South Platte River Valley between Fort Saint Vrain in the Nebraska Territory and the Cherry Creek Diggings in the Kansas Territory.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Jack Henderson eventually returned to eastern Kansas and fought for the Union in the American Civil War.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Henderson Island is today the site of the Riverdale Regional Park, formerly known as the Adams County Regional Park and Fairgrounds.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] The eastern portion of the Kansas Territory was admitted to the Union as the State of Kansas on January 29, 1861, and on February 28, 1861, the remaining western portion of the territory was made part of the new Colorado Territory.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] The Colorado Territory created Arapahoe County, on November 1, 1861, and Colorado was admitted to the Union on August 1, 1876.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] In 1901, the Colorado General Assembly voted to split Arapahoe County into three parts: a new Adams County, a new consolidated City and County of Denver, and the remainder of the Arapahoe County to be renamed South Arapahoe County.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] A ruling by the Colorado Supreme Court, subsequent legislation, and a referendum delayed the creation of Adams County until November 15, 1902.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Governor James Bradley Orman designated Brighton as the temporary Adams County Seat.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Adams County originally stretched 160 miles (260 kilometers) from present-day Sheridan Boulevard to the Kansas state border.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] On May 12, 1903, the eastern 88 miles (142 kilometers)-wide section of Adams County was transferred to the new Washington County and the new Yuma County, reducing the length of Adams County to the present 72 miles (116 kilometers) and its area to the present 1,184 square miles (3,070 km2).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] On November 8, 1904, Adams County voters chose Brighton as the permanent county seat.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] A 1989 vote transferred 53 square miles (140 square kilometers) of Adams County to the City and County of Denver for the proposed Denver International Airport, leaving the densely populated western portion of the county as two oddly-shaped peninsulas.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Adams County lost the tip of its northwest corner when the consolidated City and County of Broomfield was created on November 15, 2001.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Census Bureau, the county has a total area of 1,184 square miles (3,070 km2), of which 1,168 square miles (3,030 km2) is land and 16 square miles (41 km2) (1.4%) is water.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Adams County surrounds (and surrendered the land for) most of Denver International Airport which are in the City and County of Denver.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] As of the 2020 census, the county had a population of 519,572.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Of the residents, 25.7% were under the age of 18 and 11.1% were 65 years of age or older; the median age was 34.4 years.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] For every 100 females there were 101.9 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 100.9 males.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] 96.0% of residents lived in urban areas and 4.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] The racial makeup of the county was 55.8% White, 3.4% Black or African American, 1.8% American Indian and Alaska Native, 4.5% Asian, 0.2% Native Hawaiian and Pacific Islander, 16.8% from some other race, and 17.6% from two or more races.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Hispanic or Latino residents of any race comprised 41.7% of the population.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] There were 178,525 households in the county, of which 38.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them and 23.6% had a female householder with no spouse or partner present.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] About 20.9% of all households were made up of individuals and 7.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] There were 186,544 housing units, of which 4.3% were vacant.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Among occupied housing units, 66.5% were owner-occupied and 33.5% were renter-occupied.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.0% and the rental vacancy rate was 6.9%.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] As of the 2000 census, there were 363,857 people, 128,156 households, and 92,144 families residing in the county.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] The population density was 305 people per square mile (118 people/km2).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] There were 132,594 housing units at an average density of 111 per square mile (43/km2).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] The racial makeup of the county was 77.29% White, 2.97% Black or African American, 1.19% Native American, 3.21% Asian, 0.12% Pacific Islander, 11.73% from other races, and 3.49% from two or more races.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] 28.19% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] There were 128,156 households, out of which 37.80% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 53.80% were married couples living together, 12.10% had a female householder with no husband present, and 28.10% were non-families.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] 21.20% of all households were made up of individuals, and 5.50% had someone who was 65 years of age or older living alone.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] The average household size was 2.81 and the average family size was 3.27.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] In the county, the population was spread out, with 28.60% under the age of 18, 10.30% from 18 to 24, 34.00% from 25 to 44, 19.40% from 45 to 64, and 7.80% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] For every 100 females, there were 102.80 males.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 102.10 males.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] The median income for a household in the county was $47,323, and the median income for a family was $52,517.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Males had a median income of $36,499 versus $28,053 for females.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] The per capita income for the county was $19,944.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] About 6.50% of families and 8.90% of the population were below the poverty line, including 10.90% of those under age 18 and 7.30% of those age 65 or over.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] In 2000, the largest denominational groups were Catholics (with 60,429 members) and Evangelical Protestants (with 25,552 members).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] The largest religious bodies were the Catholic Church (with 60,429 adherents) and the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (with 6,808 adherents).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Adams County has a Board of Commissioners that operate as a collective governing board.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] There are five members that form the Board of Commissioners with each elected to represent a district or portion of the county.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] There are other elected officials that oversee an aspect or department of county operations.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Adams County lies within the 17th Judicial District which is represented by District Attorney Brian Mason.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Adams County is predominately Democratic, not having voted Republican since Ronald Reagan in 1984.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] In 2016, Hillary Clinton won the county without a majority, becoming the first Democrat to do so since her husband Bill Clinton in 1992.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] In the 2020 election, Joe Biden easily won the county with a majority of the vote, a percentage similar to Barack Obama in 2012 and 2008 but with a much larger vote count.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Despite its Democratic majority, Adams County is significantly less Democratic than most other counties in the Denver metro area, frequently swinging towards the national trend.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Despite Biden's overwhelming victory in 2020, the county swung hard back towards Trump in 2024, reducing the Democratic margin of victory from nearly 20% to under 10%.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] This came even as Colorado failed to swing as hard as most other states.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] The county is also home to the Westminster campus of Front Range Community College, the largest community college by enrollment in Colorado.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Up until 1999 when Colorado ceased coding license plates by county, Adams County used the following codes on license plates issued to passenger vehicles: TE-UF, GA-GG, SAA-SEW, and SEY-TZZ.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/adams-county-colorado] Adams County was featured as the fictional rival of South Park's peewee hockey team in the *South Park* episode "Stanley's Cup".
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Algae are polyphyletic as they do not share a common ancestor.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Although algae with two-membraned chloroplasts seem to form a paraphyletic group within the clade Archaeplastida, other algae with chloroplasts that have three or more membranes evolved from protists that acquired photosynthesis after engulfing archaeplastids.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Most algae are single-celled organisms without roots, leaves, or stems.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Most are photoautotrophs and the main primary producers of aquatic ecosystems, although some are mixotrophs that derive metabolic energy both from internal photosynthesis and from foraging external nutrients.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Some unicellular algae have become heterotrophs or parasites, relying entirely on external energy sources.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Algae have photosynthetic machinery ultimately derived from cyanobacteria that produce oxygen by splitting water molecules, unlike photosynthetic bacteria.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Fossilized filamentous algae from the Vindhya basin have been dated to 1.6 to 1.7 billion years ago.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Because of the wide range of types of algae, there is a correspondingly wide range of industrial and traditional applications in human society.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Traditional seaweed farming practices have existed for thousands of years and have strong traditions in East Asian food cultures.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] More modern algaculture applications extend the food traditions for other applications, including cattle feed, using algae for bioremediation or pollution control, transforming sunlight into algae fuels or other chemicals used in industrial processes, and in medical and scientific applications.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The singular *alga* is the Latin word for "seaweed" and retains that meaning in English.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Although some speculate that it is related to Latin *algēre*, "be cold", no reason is known to associate seaweed with temperature.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] A more likely source is *alliga*, "binding, entwining".
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The Ancient Greek word for "seaweed" was φῦκος (*phŷkos*), which could mean either the seaweed (probably red algae) or a red dye derived from it.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The Latinization, *fūcus*, meant primarily the cosmetic rouge.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The etymology is uncertain, but a strong candidate has long been some word related to the Biblical פוך (*pūk*), "paint" (if not that word itself), a cosmetic eye-shadow used by the Ancient Egyptians and other inhabitants of the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] It could be any color: black, red, green, or blue.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The study of algae is most commonly called phycology (from Greek *phykos* 'seaweed'); the term algology is falling out of use.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The algae are a heterogeneous group of mostly photosynthetic organisms that produce oxygen and lack the reproductive features and structural complexity of land plants.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] This concept includes the cyanobacteria, which are prokaryotes, and all photosynthetic protists, which are eukaryotes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] They contain chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment, and generally inhabit aquatic environments.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] However, there are many exceptions to this definition.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Many non-photosynthetic protists are included in the study of algae, such as the heterotrophic relatives of euglenophytes or the numerous species of colorless algae that have lost their chlorophyll during evolution (e.g., *Prototheca*).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Some exceptional species of algae tolerate dry terrestrial habitats, such as soil, rocks, or caves hidden from light sources, although they still need enough moisture to become active.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] A range of algal morphologies is exhibited, and convergence of features in unrelated groups is common.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The only groups to exhibit three-dimensional multicellular thalli are the reds and browns, and some chlorophytes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Apical growth is constrained to subsets of these groups: the florideophyte reds, various browns, and the charophytes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The form of charophytes is quite different from those of reds and browns, because they have distinct nodes, separated by internode 'stems'; whorls of branches reminiscent of the horsetails occur at the nodes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Conceptacles are another polyphyletic trait; they appear in the coralline algae and the Hildenbrandiales, as well as the browns.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Most of the simpler algae are unicellular flagellates or amoeboids, but colonial and nonmotile forms have developed independently among several of the groups.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] In three lines, even higher levels of organization have been reached, with full tissue differentiation.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] These are the brown algae,—some of which may reach 50 m in length (kelps)—the red algae, and the green algae.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The most complex forms are found among the charophyte algae (see Charales and Charophyta), in a lineage that eventually led to the higher land plants.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The innovation that defines these nonalgal plants is the presence of female reproductive organs with protective cell layers that protect the zygote and developing embryo.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Hence, the land plants are referred to as the Embryophytes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The term algal turf is commonly used but poorly defined.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Algal turfs are thick, carpet-like beds of seaweed that retain sediment and compete with foundation species like corals and kelps, and they are usually less than 15 cm tall.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Such a turf may consist of one or more species, and will generally cover an area in the order of a square metre or more.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Many algae, particularly species of the Characeae, have served as model experimental organisms to understand the mechanisms of the water permeability of membranes, osmoregulation, salt tolerance, cytoplasmic streaming, and the generation of action potentials.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Plant hormones are found not only in higher plants, but in algae, too.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Rhodophyta, Chlorophyta, and Heterokontophyta, the three main algal divisions, have life cycles which show considerable variation and complexity.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] In general, an asexual phase exists where the seaweed's cells are diploid, a sexual phase where the cells are haploid, followed by fusion of the male and female gametes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Asexual reproduction permits efficient population increases, but less variation is possible.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Commonly, in sexual reproduction of unicellular and colonial algae, two specialized, sexually compatible, haploid gametes make physical contact and fuse to form a zygote.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] To ensure a successful mating, the development and release of gametes is highly synchronized and regulated; pheromones may play a key role in these processes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Sexual reproduction allows for more variation and provides the benefit of efficient recombinational repair of DNA damage during meiosis, a key stage of the sexual cycle.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] However, sexual reproduction is more costly than asexual reproduction.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Meiosis has been shown to occur in many different species of algae.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Linnaeus, in *Species Plantarum* (1753), the starting point for modern botanical nomenclature, recognized 14 genera of algae, of which only four are currently considered among algae.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] In *Systema Naturae*, Linnaeus described the genera *Volvox* and *Corallina*, and a species of *Acetabularia* (as *Madrepora*), among the animals.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] In 1768, Samuel Gottlieb Gmelin (1744–1774) published the *Historia Fucorum*, the first work dedicated to marine algae and the first book on marine biology to use the then new binomial nomenclature of Linnaeus.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] It included elaborate illustrations of seaweed and marine algae on folded leaves.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Harvey (1811–1866) and Lamouroux (1813) were the first to divide macroscopic algae into four divisions based on their pigmentation.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] This is the first use of a biochemical criterion in plant systematics.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Harvey's four divisions are: red algae (Rhodospermae), brown algae (Melanospermae), green algae (Chlorospermae), and Diatomaceae.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] At this time, microscopic algae were discovered and reported by a different group of workers (e.g., O.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Müller and Ehrenberg) studying the Infusoria (microscopic organisms).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Unlike macroalgae, which were clearly viewed as plants, microalgae were frequently considered animals because they are often motile.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Even the nonmotile (coccoid) microalgae were sometimes merely seen as stages of the lifecycle of plants, macroalgae, or animals.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Although used as a taxonomic category in some pre-Darwinian classifications, e.g., Linnaeus (1753), de Jussieu (1789), Lamouroux (1813), Harvey (1836), Horaninow (1843), Agassiz (1859), Wilson & Cassin (1864), in further classifications, the "algae" are seen as an artificial, polyphyletic group.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Throughout the 20th century, most classifications treated the following groups as divisions or classes of algae: cyanophytes, rhodophytes, chrysophytes, xanthophytes, bacillariophytes, phaeophytes, pyrrhophytes (cryptophytes and dinophytes), euglenophytes, and chlorophytes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] With the abandonment of plant-animal dichotomous classification, most groups of algae (sometimes all) were included in Protista, later also abandoned in favour of Eukaryota.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] However, as a legacy of the older plant life scheme, some groups that were also treated as protozoans in the past still have duplicated classifications (see ambiregnal protists).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] In other cases, some groups were originally characterized as parasitic algae (e.g., *Chlorochytrium*), but later were seen as endophytic algae.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Some filamentous bacteria (e.g., *Beggiatoa*) were originally seen as algae.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Furthermore, groups like the apicomplexans are also parasites derived from ancestors that possessed plastids, but are not included in any group traditionally seen as algae.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The most recent estimate (as of January 2024) documents 50,605 living and 10,556 fossil algal species, according to the online database AlgaeBase.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] They are classified into 15 phyla or divisions.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Some phyla are not photosynthetic, namely Picophyta and Rhodelphidophyta, but they are included in the database due to their close relationship with red algae.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The various algal phyla can be differentiated according to several biological traits.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] They have distinct morphologies, photosynthetic pigmentation, storage products, cell wall composition, and mechanisms of carbon concentration.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Some phyla have unique cellular structures.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] , the most common genus of cyanobacteria.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Among prokaryotes, five major groups of bacteria have evolved the ability to photosynthesize, including heliobacteria, green sulfur and nonsulfur bacteria and proteobacteria.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] However, the only lineage where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved is in the cyanobacteria, often known as blue-green algae for their blue-green (cyan) coloration.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] They are classified as the phylum Cyanobacteriota or Cyanophyta.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] However, this phylum also includes two classes of non-photosynthetic bacteria: Melainabacteria (also called Vampirovibrionia or Vampirovibrionophyceae) and Sericytochromatia (also known as Blackallbacteria).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] A third class contains the photosynthetic ones, known as Cyanophyceae (also called Cyanobacteriia or Oxyphotobacteria).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] As bacteria, their cells lack membrane-bound organelles, with the exception of thylakoids.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Like other algae, cyanobacteria have chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Their accessory pigments include phycobilins (phycoerythrobilin and phycocyanobilin), carotenoids and, in some cases, *b*, *d*, or *f* chlorophylls, generally distributed in phycobilisomes found in the surface of thylakoids.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] They display a variety of body forms, such as single cells, colonies, and unbranched or branched filaments.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Their cells are commonly covered in a sheath of mucilage, and they also have a typical gram-negative bacterial cell wall composed largely of peptidoglycan.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] They have various storage particles, including cyanophycin as aminoacid and nitrogen reserves, "cyanophycean starch" (similar to plant amylose) for carbohydrates, and lipid droplets.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Their Rubisco enzymes are concentrated in carboxysomes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] They occupy a diverse array of aquatic and terrestrial habitats, including extreme environments from hot springs to polar glaciers.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Some are subterranean, living via hydrogen-based lithoautotrophy instead of photosynthesis.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Three lineages of cyanobacteria, *Prochloraceae*, *Prochlorothrix* and *Prochlorococcus*, independently evolved to have chlorophylls *a* and *b* instead of phycobilisomes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Due to their different pigmentation, they were historically grouped in a separate division, Prochlorophyta, as this is the typical pigmentation seen in green algae (e.g., chlorophytes).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Eventually, this classification became obsolete, as it is a polyphyletic grouping.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Cyanobacteria are included as algae by most phycological sources and by the International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants, although a few authors exclude them from the definition of algae and reserve the term for eukaryotes only.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Eukaryotic algae contain chloroplasts that are similar in structure to cyanobacteria.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Chloroplasts contain circular DNA like that in cyanobacteria and are interpreted as representing reduced endosymbiotic cyanobacteria.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] However, the exact origin of the chloroplasts is different among separate lineages of algae, reflecting their acquisition during different endosymbiotic events.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Many groups contain some members that are no longer photosynthetic.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Some retain plastids, but not chloroplasts, while others have lost plastids entirely.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Primary algae are those with "primary chloroplasts", i.e. chloroplasts with two membranes, evolved through a single symbiogenetic event with an endosymbiont β-cyanobacterium as early as 1.6 Gya during the Mesoproterozoic.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] These algae are mainly grouped in the clade Archaeplastida (meaning "ancient plastid"), which includes the major groups Viridiplantae (green algae *sensu lato* and all land plants) and Rhodophyta (red algae) as well as the minor group Glaucophyta (grey algae).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Land plants (embryophytes) are pigmented similarly to green algae and likely evolved from the freshwater green algae clade Streptophyta, which is sister taxon to Chlorophyta (green algae *sensu stricto*) and the basal clade Prasinodermophyta.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] There is also a minor group of amoeboid protists with primary plastids evolved via different origin and at a much later date than archaeplastid chloroplasts.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The four species of the euglyphid amoebae genus *Paulinella*, have cyanobionts (known as cyanelles) that perform photosynthesis, likely originated from the endosymbiosis of a α-cyanobacterium (probably an ancestral member of Chroococcales), about 90–140 Mya during the Cretaceous.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Secondary algae are eukaryotes with "secondary chloroplasts", i.e. those evolved from phagocytosis and subsequent endosymbiosis of primary algae (mainly green or red algae) or other secondary algae, thus "stealing" the endosymbionts' photosynthetic capability.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] As a result, these algae have chloroplasts surrounded by three or more membranes, and appeared independently in various distantly related protist lineages.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Two lineages of secondary algae, chlorarachniophytes and euglenophytes have "green" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *b*.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Their chloroplasts are surrounded by four and three membranes, respectively, and were probably retained from ingested green algae.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Other groups have "red" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *c*, and phycobilins.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The shape can vary; they may be of discoid, plate-like, reticulate, cup-shaped, spiral, or ribbon shaped.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] They have one or more pyrenoids to preserve protein and starch.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The latter chlorophyll type is not known from any prokaryotes or primary chloroplasts, but genetic similarities with red algae suggest a relationship there.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The typical dinoflagellate chloroplast has three membranes, but considerable diversity exists in chloroplasts within the group, and a number of endosymbiotic events apparently occurred.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The Apicomplexa, a group of closely related parasites, also have plastids called apicoplasts, which are not photosynthetic.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The Chromerida are the closest relatives of apicomplexans, and some have retained their chloroplasts.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The three alveolate groups evolved from a common myzozoan ancestor that obtained chloroplasts.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The distribution of algal species has been fairly well studied since the founding of phytogeography in the mid-19th century.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Algae spread mainly by the dispersal of spores analogously to the dispersal of cryptogamic plants by spores.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Spores can be found in a variety of environments: fresh and marine waters, air, soil, and in or on other organisms.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Whether a spore is to grow into an adult organism depends on the species and the environmental conditions where the spore lands.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The spores of freshwater algae are dispersed mainly by running water and wind, as well as by living carriers.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] However, not all bodies of water can carry all species of algae, as the chemical composition of certain water bodies limits the algae that can survive within them.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Marine spores are often spread by ocean currents.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Ocean water presents many vastly different habitats based on temperature and nutrient availability, resulting in phytogeographic zones, regions, and provinces.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] To some degree, the distribution of algae is subject to floristic discontinuities caused by geographical features, such as Antarctica, long distances of ocean or general land masses.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] It is, therefore, possible to identify species occurring by locality, such as "Pacific algae" or "North Sea algae".
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] When they occur out of their localities, hypothesizing a transport mechanism is usually possible, such as the hulls of ships.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] For example, *Ulva reticulata* and *U. fasciata* travelled from the mainland to Hawaii in this manner.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Mapping is possible for select species only: "there are many valid examples of confined distribution patterns." For example, *Clathromorphum* is an arctic genus and is not mapped far south of there.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] For example, according to one standard textbook, in the British Isles, the *UK Biodiversity Steering Group Report* estimated there to be 20,000 algal species in the UK.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Another checklist reports only about 5,000 species.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] and so on, but lacking any scientific basis or reliable sources, these numbers have no more credibility than the British ones mentioned above.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Most estimates also omit microscopic algae, such as phytoplankton.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Algae are prominent in bodies of water, common in terrestrial environments, and are found in unusual environments, such as on snow and ice.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Seaweeds grow mostly in shallow marine waters, less than 100 m (330 ft) deep; however, some such as *Navicula pennata* have been recorded to a depth of 360 m (1,180 ft).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] A type of algae, *Ancylonema nordenskioeldii*, was found in Greenland in areas known as the 'Dark Zone', which caused an increase in the rate of melting ice sheet.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The same algae was found in the Italian Alps, after pink ice appeared on parts of the Presena glacier.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The various sorts of algae play significant roles in aquatic ecology.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Microscopic forms that live suspended in the water column (phytoplankton) provide the food base for most marine food chains.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] In very high densities (algal blooms), these algae may discolor the water and outcompete, poison, or asphyxiate other life forms.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Algae can be used as indicator organisms to monitor pollution in various aquatic systems.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] In many cases, algal metabolism is sensitive to various pollutants.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Due to this, the species composition of algal populations may shift in the presence of chemical pollutants.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] To detect these changes, algae can be sampled from the environment and maintained in laboratories with relative ease.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Some species of algae form symbiotic relationships with other organisms.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] In these symbioses, the algae supply photosynthates (organic substances) to the host organism providing protection to the algal cells.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The host organism derives some or all of its energy requirements from the algae.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Lichens are defined by the International Association for Lichenology to be "an association of a fungus and a photosynthetic symbiont resulting in a stable vegetative body having a specific structure".
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The fungi, or mycobionts, are mainly from the Ascomycota with a few from the Basidiomycota.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] In nature, they do not occur separate from lichens.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] It is unknown when they began to associate.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] One or more mycobiont associates with the same phycobiont species, from the green algae, except that alternatively, the mycobiont may associate with a species of cyanobacteria (hence "photobiont" is the more accurate term).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] A photobiont may be associated with many different mycobionts or may live independently; accordingly, lichens are named and classified as fungal species.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The association is termed a morphogenesis because the lichen has a form and capabilities not possessed by the symbiont species alone (they can be experimentally isolated).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The photobiont possibly triggers otherwise latent genes in the mycobiont.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Trentepohlia is an example of a common green alga genus worldwide that can grow on its own or be lichenised.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Lichen thus share some of the habitat and often similar appearance with specialized species of algae (*aerophytes*) growing on exposed surfaces such as tree trunks and rocks and sometimes discoloring them.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Coral reefs are accumulated from the calcareous exoskeletons of marine invertebrates of the order Scleractinia (stony corals).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] These animals metabolize sugar and oxygen to obtain energy for their cell-building processes, including secretion of the exoskeleton, with water and carbon dioxide as byproducts.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Dinoflagellates (algal protists) are often endosymbionts in the cells of the coral-forming marine invertebrates, where they accelerate host-cell metabolism by generating sugar and oxygen immediately available through photosynthesis using incident light and the carbon dioxide produced by the host.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Reef-building stony corals (hermatypic corals) require endosymbiotic algae from the genus *Symbiodinium* to be in a healthy condition.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The loss of *Symbiodinium* from the host is known as coral bleaching, a condition which leads to the deterioration of a reef.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Endosymbiontic green algae live close to the surface of some sponges, for example, breadcrumb sponges (*Halichondria panicea*).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The alga is thus protected from predators; the sponge is provided with oxygen and sugars which can account for 50 to 80% of sponge growth in some species.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Prokaryotic algae, i.e., cyanobacteria, are the only group of organisms where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of cyanobacteria is dated at 2100 million years ago, although stromatolites, associated with cyanobacterial biofilms, appear as early as 3500 million years ago in the fossil record.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Eukaryotic algae are polyphyletic thus their origin cannot be traced back to a single hypothetical common ancestor.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] It is thought that they came into existence when photosynthetic coccoid cyanobacteria got phagocytized by a unicellular heterotrophic eukaryote (a protist), giving rise to double-membranous primary plastids.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Such symbiogenic events (primary symbiogenesis) are believed to have occurred more than 1.5 billion years ago during the Calymmian period, early in Boring Billion, but it is difficult to track the key events because of so much time gap.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] This process of serial cell "capture" and "enslavement" explains the diversity of photosynthetic eukaryotes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of eukaryotic algae is *Bangiomorpha pubescens*, a red alga found in rocks around 1047 million years old.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Recent genomic and phylogenomic approaches have significantly clarified plastid genome evolution, the horizontal movement of endosymbiont genes to the "host" nuclear genome, and plastid spread throughout the eukaryotic tree of life.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] It is accepted that both euglenophytes and chlorarachniophytes obtained their chloroplasts from chlorophytes that became endosymbionts.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] In particular, euglenophyte chloroplasts share the most resemblance with the genus *Pyramimonas*.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] However, there is still no clear order in which the secondary and tertiary endosymbioses occurred for the "chromist" lineages (ochrophytes, cryptophytes, haptophytes and myzozoans).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Two main models have been proposed to explain the order, both of which agree that cryptophytes obtained their chloroplasts from red algae.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] One model, hypothesized in 2014 by John W.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Stiller and coauthors, suggests that a cryptophyte became the plastid of ochrophytes, which in turn became the plastid of myzozoans and haptophytes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The other model, suggested by Andrzej Bodył and coauthors in 2009, describes that a cryptophyte became the plastid of both haptophytes and ochrophytes, and it is a haptophyte that became the plastid of myzozoans instead.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] These charophyte algae probably already developed filamentous thalli and holdfasts that superficially resembled plant stems and roots, and probably had an isomorphic alternation of generations.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] They perhaps evolved some 850 mya and might even be as early as 1 Gya during the late phase of the Boring Billion.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Algaculture is a form of aquaculture involving the farming of species of algae.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The majority of algae that are intentionally cultivated fall into the category of microalgae (also referred to as phytoplankton, microphytes, or planktonic algae).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Global production of farmed aquatic plants, overwhelmingly dominated by seaweeds, grew in output volume from 13.5 million tonnes in 1995, to just over 30 million tonnes in 2016 and 37.8 million tonnes in 2022 and 40 million tonnes in 2024.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] This increase was the result of production expansions led by China, followed by Malaysia, the Philippines, the United Republic of Tanzania, and the Russian Federation.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Cultured microalgae already contribute to a wide range of sectors in the emerging bioeconomy.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Research suggests there are large potentials and benefits of algaculture for the development of a future healthy and sustainable food system.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Seaweed farming or kelp farming is the practice of cultivating and harvesting seaweed.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] In its simplest form farmers gather from natural beds, while at the other extreme farmers fully control the crop's life cycle.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The seven most cultivated taxa are *Eucheuma* spp., *Kappaphycus alvarezii*, *Gracilaria* spp., *Saccharina japonica*, *Undaria pinnatifida*, *Pyropia* spp., and *Sargassum fusiforme*.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] *Eucheuma* and *K. alvarezii* are attractive for carrageenan (a gelling agent); *Gracilaria* is farmed for agar; the rest are eaten after limited processing.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Seaweeds are different from mangroves and seagrasses, as they are photosynthetic algal organisms and are non-flowering.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The largest seaweed-producing countries as of 2022 are China (58.62%) and Indonesia (28.6%); followed by South Korea (5.09%) and the Philippines (4.19%).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Seaweed farming has frequently been developed to improve economic conditions and to reduce fishing pressure.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that world production in 2019 was over 35 million tonnes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] North America produced some 23,000 tonnes of wet seaweed.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Alaska, Maine, France, and Norway each more than doubled their seaweed production since 2018*.* As of 2019, seaweed represented 30% of marine aquaculture.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] In 2023, the global seaweed extract market was valued at $16.5 billion, with strong projected growth.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Seaweed farming is a carbon negative crop, with a high potential for climate change mitigation.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate recommends "further research attention" as a mitigation tactic.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] World Wildlife Fund, Oceans 2050, and The Nature Conservancy publicly support expanded seaweed cultivation.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] An algae bioreactor is used for cultivating micro or macroalgae.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Algae may be cultivated for the purposes of biomass production (as in a seaweed cultivator), wastewater treatment, CO2 fixation, or aquarium/pond filtration in the form of an algae scrubber.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Algae bioreactors vary widely in design, falling broadly into two categories: open reactors and enclosed reactors.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Open reactors are exposed to the atmosphere while enclosed reactors, also commonly called photobioreactors, are isolated to varying extents from the atmosphere.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Specifically, algae bioreactors can be used to produce fuels such as biodiesel and bioethanol, to generate animal feed, or to reduce pollutants such as NOx and CO2 in flue gases of power plants.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Fundamentally, this kind of bioreactor is based on the photosynthetic reaction, which is performed by the chlorophyll-containing algae itself using dissolved carbon dioxide and sunlight.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The carbon dioxide is dispersed into the reactor fluid to make it accessible to the algae.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The bioreactor has to be made out of transparent material.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] To be competitive and independent from fluctuating support from (local) policy on the long run, biofuels should equal or beat the cost level of fossil fuels.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Here, algae-based fuels hold great promise, directly related to the potential to produce more biomass per unit area in a year than any other form of biomass.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The break-even point for algae-based biofuels is estimated to occur by 2025.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Today, algae are used by humans in many ways; for example, as fertilizers, soil conditioners, and livestock feed.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Aquatic and microscopic species are cultured in clear tanks or ponds and are either harvested or used to treat effluents pumped through the ponds.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Algaculture on a large scale is an important type of aquaculture in some places.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Maerl is commonly used as a soil conditioner.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Algae are used as foods in many countries: China consumes more than 70 species, including *fat choy*, a cyanobacterium considered a vegetable; Japan, over 20 species such as *nori* and *aonori*; Ireland, dulse; Chile, cochayuyo.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Laver is used to make laverbread in Wales, where it is known as *bara lawr*.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] In Korea, green laver is used to make *gim*.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The oils from some algae have high levels of unsaturated fatty acids.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Some varieties of algae favored by vegetarianism and veganism contain the long-chain, essential omega-3 fatty acids, docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) and eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Fish oil contains the omega-3 fatty acids, but the original source is algae (microalgae in particular), which are eaten by marine life such as copepods and are passed up the food chain.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The natural pigments (carotenoids and chlorophylls) produced by algae can be used as alternatives to chemical dyes and coloring agents.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Carrageenan, from the red alga *Chondrus crispus*, is used as a thickener and stabilizer in milk products.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Agar, a gelatinous substance derived from red algae, has a number of commercial uses.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] It is a good medium on which to grow bacteria and fungi, as most microorganisms cannot digest agar.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Alginic acid, or alginate, is extracted from brown algae.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Its uses range from gelling agents in food, to medical dressings.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Alginic acid also has been used in the field of biotechnology as a biocompatible medium for cell encapsulation and cell immobilization.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Molecular cuisine is also a user of the substance for its gelling properties, by which it becomes a delivery vehicle for flavours.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Between 100,000 and 170,000 wet tons of *Macrocystis* are harvested annually in New Mexico for alginate extraction and abalone feed.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Agricultural Research Service scientists found that 60–90% of nitrogen runoff and 70–100% of phosphorus runoff can be captured from manure effluents using a horizontal algae scrubber, also called an algal turf scrubber (ATS).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Scientists developed the ATS, which consists of shallow, 30-metre (100 ft) raceways of nylon netting where algae colonies can form, and studied its efficacy for three years.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] They found that algae can readily be used to reduce the nutrient runoff from agricultural fields and increase the quality of water flowing into rivers, streams, and oceans.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Researchers collected and dried the nutrient-rich algae from the ATS and studied its potential as an organic fertilizer.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] They found that cucumber and corn seedlings grew just as well using ATS organic fertilizer as they did with commercial fertilizers.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Algae scrubbers, using bubbling upflow or vertical waterfall versions, are now also being used to filter aquaria and ponds.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The alga *Stichococcus bacillaris* has been seen to colonize silicone resins used at archaeological sites; biodegrading the synthetic substance.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Various polymers can be created from algae, which can be especially useful in the creation of bioplastics.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] These include hybrid plastics, cellulose-based plastics, poly-lactic acid, and bio-polyethylene.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Several companies have begun to produce algae polymers commercially, including for use in flip-flops and in surf boards.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] Even algae is also used to prepare various polymeric resins suitable for coating applications.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/algae] The third island on Kunming Lake at Beijing's Summer Palace is called Zaojian Tang Dao (藻鑒堂島).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The **American National Red Cross**, sometimes referred to as **ANRC**, is an American nonprofit humanitarian organization that provides emergency assistance, disaster relief, and disaster preparedness education in the United States.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Clara Barton founded the organization in 1881 after initially learning of the Red Cross, founded 1863 in Geneva, Switzerland.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] It is the designated American affiliate of the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies and the International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The organization has provided services after many notable disasters, including the sinking of the RMS *Titanic* in 1912, World War I, the Spanish flu pandemic of 1918, World War II, Hurricane Katrina, and the Maui wildfires of 2023.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] It also provides blood banking services.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Clara Barton established the American Red Cross in Dansville, New York, on May 21, 1881, and was also the organization's first president.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] She organized a meeting on May 12 of that year at the house of Senator Omar D.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Fifteen people were present at the meeting, Conger and Representative William Lawrence (R, OH) (who became the first vice president) to discuss the start of the American Red Cross.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The first local chapter was established in 1881 at the English Evangelical Lutheran Church of Dansville.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Jane Delano (1862–1919) founded the American Red Cross Nursing Service on January 20, 1910.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Barton founded the American chapter after learning of the Red Cross in Geneva, Switzerland.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In 1869, she went to Europe and became involved in the work of the International Red Cross during the Franco-Prussian War.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] She was determined to bring the organization to America.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Barton became President of the American branch of the society, known as the American National Red Cross, in May 1881 in Washington.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The first chapters opened in upstate New York, where she had connections.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Rockefeller and four others donated money to help create a national headquarters near the White House.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The abolitionist Frederick Douglass, a friend of Barton's, offered advice and support as she sought to establish the American chapter of Red Cross.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] As Register of Deeds for the District of Columbia, Douglass also signed the American Red Cross's original Articles of Incorporation.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The next major disaster was the Johnstown Flood on May 31, 1889.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] More than 2,200 people died, and thousands more were injured in or near Johnstown, Pennsylvania, in one of the worst disasters in U.S. history.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Clara and 5 other Red Cross workers arrived, and within days they assembled 45 others, including doctors and nurses, to assist in disaster relief.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The organization received donations from around the world, and Clara didn't leave the site for 5 months.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Many within the organization became frustrated with Barton's leadership style, and Barton resigned from the organization in 1904.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Professional social work experts took control and made the group a model of Progressive Era scientific reform.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] New leader Mabel Thorp Boardman consulted with senior government officials, military officers, social workers, and financiers.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] William Howard Taft was especially influential.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] They imposed an ethos of "managerialism", transforming the agency from Barton's cult of personality to an "organizational humanitarianism" ready for expansion.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Among the notable disasters of the Progressive Era that featured American Red Cross involvement was the sinking of the RMS *Titanic* in 1912.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The New York City chapter joined with the Charity Organization Society to provide funds to survivors and the dependents of those who perished.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The organization was active during World War I.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Among its activities in Paris was the Studio for Portrait Masks, which fashioned galvanized-copper face masks for soldiers who had been facially disfigured during the war.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] During World War Two, the American Red Cross ran the Booker T Washington Service Club in Sydney, Australia.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Recent presidents and CEO s include Gail J.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] McGovern, Cliff Holtz, Elizabeth Dole, Bernadine Healy, Mary S.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In 2007, U.S. legislation clarified the role for the Board of Governors and that of the senior management in the wake of difficulties following Hurricane Katrina.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Members of the board of governors other than the chairman are elected at the annual meeting of chapter delegates.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The board appoints the chief executive officer.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The president and CEOs' overall goal is to execute the Red Cross' strategies and missions and to lead and oversee the business activities that the Red Cross partakes in or organizes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] As of April 2023, the American Red Cross scores four out of four stars at Charity Navigator and A− at CharityWatch.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In 1996, the *Chronicle of Philanthropy*, an industry magazine, released the results of the largest study of charitable and nonprofit organization popularity and credibility.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The study showed that ARC was ranked as the third "most popular charity/non-profit in America" of over 100 charities researched, with 48% of Americans over age 12 choosing "Love" or "Like A lot" to describe it.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC supplies roughly 45% of the donated blood in the United States, which it sells to hospitals and regional suppliers on a cost-recovery basis.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In 2019, hospitals paid blood collection centers about $215 per unit of red blood cells.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Community-based blood centers supply nearly 50% and approximately 5% is collected directly by hospitals.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In December 2004, ARC completed its largest blood processing facility in the United States in Pomona, California, on the campus grounds of California State Polytechnic University, Pomona.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] For more than 50 years, ARC provided allograft tissue for transplant through sales in its Tissue Services Program.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] It cared for thousands of donor families who donated tissue and sold the tissue to more than 1 million transplant recipients.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] At the end of January 2005, ARC ended its Tissue Services program to focus on its primary missions of Disaster Relief and Blood Services.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] A leader in the plasma industry, ARC provides more than one quarter of the USA's plasma products.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In February 1999, ARC completed its "Transformation", a $287 million program that reengineered Red Cross Blood Services' processing, testing, and distribution system and established a new management structure.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] As of 2011, ARC is no longer in the Plasma Services industry.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] It supplies Baxter BioSciences with items for manufacturing plasma products.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In 1999, ARC became one of the first American blood banks to implement nucleic acid testing (NAT).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The NAT tests for HIV and HCV are licensed by the U.S.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Leukocytes (white blood cells) help fight off foreign substances such as bacteria, viruses, and abnormal cells.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In fact, these foreign leukocytes in transfused red blood cells and platelets are often not well tolerated and have been associated with some types of transfusion complications.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Leukocytes in stored blood products can have a variety of biological effects, including depression of immune function, which can result in organ failure and death.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Because whole blood is rarely used for transfusion and not kept in routine inventory, leukoreduced red blood supplies are critical.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] After collection, the whole blood is separated into red cells and plasma by a centrifuge.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] A preservative solution is mixed with the red cells and the component is filtered with a leukoreduction filter.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The shelf life of this product is 42 days.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC is moving toward system-wide universal prestorage leukocyte reduction to improve patient care.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] From 1976 to 1985, the FDA received reports of 355 fatalities associated with transfusion, 99 of which were excluded from further review because they were unrelated to transfusion or involved hepatitis or HIV/AIDS.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] While the FDA has not yet made leukoreduction a requirement, ARC took a leading role in implementing this procedure with a goal of leukoreducing all blood products.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] More than 70% of ARC red blood cell components undergo prestorage leukoreduction, a filtering process performed soon after blood is donated.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Holland blood laboratory in Rockville, Maryland.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC offers various cellular therapies; these treatments involve collecting and treating blood cells from a patient or other blood donor.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The treated cells are introduced into a patient to help revive normal cell function, replace cells that are lost as a result of disease, accidents or aging, or to prevent illnesses from appearing.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The ARC has implemented technology from Accellix, a biotechnology company specializing in automated cell phenotyping, in order to help meet the increasing demand and need for various cell and gene therapies.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The ARC continues to work on further expanding their help and participation in cellular therapies and are always looking for donors who are willing and able to contribute to their mission.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Training Services is one of the five divisions of the American Red Cross, responsible for providing health and safety training to the general public as well as the workforce.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In calendar year 2024 the American Red Cross trained 5.9 million people how to save lives through their programs.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In addition to basic level certifications in the above courses, the American Red Cross also offers instructor-level courses.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Instructor-level courses are designed to teach participants how to become instructors or instructor trainers for American Red Cross courses.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Instructor Trainer Academies are designed to certify current instructors to become instructor trainers, or people who can teach instructor-level courses.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Training Services has an online store where you can purchase supplies including First Aid Kits, CPR key chains, flashlights, and emergency radios.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] American Red Cross courses may be conducted by volunteers, contractors, or employees of the Red Cross, or may be conducted by American Red Cross Licensed Training Providers (LTPs) (sometimes called Training Providers).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The American Red Cross runs many of its own courses that can be conducted on land such as First Aid/CPR/AED and basic life support.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] There are a number of courses that require aquatic facilities to run, such as lifeguarding and swimming and water safety.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] These courses are generally left to Licensed Training Providers (colleges, government agencies, fire departments, community centers).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The Scientific Advisory Council is a panel including over 60 nationally and internationally recognized medical, scientific, aquatics, and academic experts from across the United States.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Sub-council members conduct and gather research all throughout the world while experts within the council study and review this research and the science behind it.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] As of late, they have learned to perfect how to access more swim resources and swim safety.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Each year, the American Red Cross responds to more than 60,000 disasters, including house or apartment fires (making up the majority), hurricanes, floods, earthquakes, tornadoes, hazardous materials spills, transportation accidents, explosions and other natural and man-made disasters.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Disaster relief focuses on emergency disaster-caused needs.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] When a disaster threatens or strikes, the American Red Cross provides shelter, food and health and mental health services (Psychological First Aid) to address basic human needs.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The core of American Red Cross disaster relief is assistance to individuals and families to enable them to resume their normal daily activities.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The organization provides translation and interpretation when necessary, and maintains a database of multilingual volunteers.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] At the local level, American Red Cross chapters operate volunteer-staffed Disaster Action Teams.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] These local volunteer teams are on call 24/7/365 to respond to the 65,000 disasters that occur every year in the United States, like home fires.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The American Red Cross feeds emergency workers of other agencies, handles inquiries from concerned family members outside the disaster area, provides blood and blood products to disaster victims and helps those affected by a disaster to access other resources.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] It is a member of National Voluntary Organizations Active in Disaster (VOAD) and works closely with other agencies such as Salvation Army and Amateur Radio Emergency Service with whom it has memorandums of understanding.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The American Red Cross works to encourage preparedness by providing important literature on readiness.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Many chapters also offer free disaster preparedness and hands-only CPR classes to the general public.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] A major misconception among the general public is that the American Red Cross provides medical facilities, engages in search and rescue operations or deploys ambulances.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Instead, first responder roles are left to government agencies as dictated by the National Response Framework.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Red Cross societies outside the U.S. may provide such functions; for example, the *Cruz Roja Mexicana* (Mexican Red Cross) runs a national ambulance service.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Furthermore, American Red Cross Emergency Response Vehicles (ERVs) look similar to ambulances.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] These ERVs instead are designed for distribution of relief supplies, such as meals, drinks and other relief supplies.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Although American Red Cross shelters usually assign a nurse to the facility, they are not equipped to provide medical care beyond first aid.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The Disaster Workforce Engagement team ensures volunteers from American Red Cross chapters and regions are tracked in a national database of responders, classified by their training, experience, and ability to serve in one or more activities within groups.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Activities include feeding, sheltering, warehousing, damage assessment, accounting, communications, public affairs, counseling and others.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Responders complete training for the specific positions they intend to serve in.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] As a National Response Framework support agency, ARC shelters, feeds and provides other types of emergency relief to victims of disasters.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] American Red Cross is a co-lead with the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) for the mass care portion of Emergency Support Function 6.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC and FEMA share responsibility for planning and coordinating mass care services with FEMA.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The American Red Cross has responsibilities for other Emergency Support Functions, such as providing health and mental health services.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In 1908 an earthquake and tsunami devastated the area surround the Strait of Messina.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The American public donated nearly $1 million to the American Red Cross which was sent to Italy via the State Department, alongside $800,000 in public funds.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The decision to use the State Department to distribute funds, rather than sending them directly to the Italian Red Cross, was indicative of the organization's shift away from the International Red Cross movement and towards US interests.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] This was the ARC's first major response to an international civilian disaster.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In December of that year two Americans, Harry Bowdoin and Charles King Wood, were in Taormina when the earthquake occurred.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Bowdoin was spending the winter in Taormina with his invalid mother and Mr.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Wood was an artist who had lived in Taormina for several years.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] These two men entered upon the work of relief answering the call of the Red Cross.[110] Afterwards, the Italian government conferred upon the two men the honorific of "Cavaliere".
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Bowdoin and Wood were two of the twenty-one recipients of the American Red Cross silver medal for "specially meritorious service" for that year.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Congress had only rarely allocated funds for natural disasters; likewise, the level of funding given to Italy was also unprecedented.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The ARC's aid to Italy carried important diplomatic meaning for the U.S. due to the large number of Italian emigrants who left for the U.S. every year, and Italy's growing importance within Europe.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC leaders viewed relief efforts in Italy as a way to demonstrate U.S. care for the nation.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Alongside this, disaster relief was seen as a tool for social reform.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] A fundamental goal of the ARC's assistance was to address the perceived threat of pulverization within an area that a large proportion of U.S. immigrants came from.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC leaders believed that humanitarian relief would be more effective in fostering goodwill and creating stability than any other action.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In 1912 the State and War Department became concerned with increasing reports of hunger within the country.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] As a result, Knox asked the ARC to supply food for non-combatants as well.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] American forces worked with the ARC to open railroads to distribute humanitarian supplies to Managua, Granada, Léon, and other key cities.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Although the ARC was a non-governmental agency, its humanitarian efforts lined up with American foreign policy, becoming a useful diplomatic mechanism for softening the effects of American military intervention and securing its political interests.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Prior to the United States entry into World War I, the American Red Cross was a neutral organization aiding both the allied and central powers.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] However, when the United States joined the allied powers, the American Red Cross aid to the central powers ended immediately.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] On May 10, 1917, President Woodrow Wilson created the American Red Cross War Council to aid funding initiatives and direct the activities of the organization.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Throughout the war, the Council raised $400 million.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] During World War I, the American Red Cross operated as a quasi-state and non-governmental organization, separate from the United States government.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Its efforts were primarily focused on civilian aid overseas, rather than domestic disaster relief.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The organization spent less than one million dollars on domestic efforts, compared to approximately $120 million allocated to overseas relief.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] It provided food, shelter, employment, and medical assistance to civilians displaced by the war.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] By the end of the war, more than one-third of the U.S. population had joined the organization, and approximately $400 million was raised in 1917 and 1918 alone.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Notable projects included the Pisa Village housing initiative in Italy, begun in 1918, and the production of 500,000 wound dressings made with Sphagnum moss as an alternative to cotton, based on research by John William Hotson.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The power of the American Red Cross was soon recognized by the Government which began to see "the value of overseas aid as a tool of statecraft".
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The American Red Cross was increasingly being used as an arm of the state to facilitate the realization of American foreign policy objects.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Principally, the American Red Cross enhanced America's image abroad while also disseminating American practices and values throughout Europe.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] It intervened in European health and welfare practices by introducing American methods.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Moreover, after the Bolsheviks seized power in Russia, President Wilson used the American Red Cross as a diplomacy tool to aid the White forces.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Wilson believed that food was the "real thing" to combat Bolshevism and ordered the American Red Cross to distribute food and material relief to Bolshevik opponents in the Russian civil war.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The American Red Cross, therefore, served the dual functions of assisting the realization of United States foreign policy objectives and promoting international humanitarianism.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] At the end of the war the League of Red Cross Societies was created.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] During the flu pandemic of 1918, American Red Cross chapters were instrumental in establishing both preventive measures and treatment plans within their local communities throughout the United States.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Active initiatives undertaken by local chapters included the sewing of masks for local distribution, the production and promotion of educational pamphlets, the establishment of localized motor corps, and providing door-to-door nursing and social services.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In some cities, the motor corps functioned both in providing auxiliary ambulatory services and expanding the logistical dispersion of manpower and supplies.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The contribution of nurses, goods, services, and local administrative guidance offered by the American Red Cross provided local community leaders with essential support in combating the pandemic.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Unlike European relief organization, which had to invest much of their time in fund-raising efforts, the American Red Cross's collaboration with Herbert Hoover's American Relief Administration had funding on a different scale and well as popular and governmental support at its disposal.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] With its membership of over 33 million Americans in 1918 (20% of the U.S. population) and its designation as the official U.S. organization for foreign relief by the Geneva Treaty and Congressional mandate, the ARC was neither wholly private nor an official governmental organization.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] This quasi-governmental support allowed the ARC to secure credibility and support that was unattainable for other relief organizations such as the YMCA or Knights of Columbus.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The ARC's private funding allowed for more flexibility than government organizations, its leaders chose to support U.S. foreign policy in many ways but also often pursued aims that differed from that of the military or political policymakers.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Hundreds of ARC workers pursued permanent reform of Italian social politics, rather than emergency relief they founded nursing schools, developed child welfare projects and waged anti-tuberculosis crusades.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In introducing these American ideas about public health and social welfare, the ARC acted as what historian Daniel T.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Rodgers had referred to as 'brokers of ideas', who facilitated transatlantic exchange on the methods and philosophies of social reform.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Work in the ARC allowed American citizens to contribute to transatlantic social reform discourse.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC workers built upon and expanded the already existing Italian efforts for social reform.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC reformers embraced a strategic cultural sensitivity as they attempted to work with Italians and help them to take control of their own social institutions.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] By presenting their reforms as mutual exchange rather than imposed change, ARC workers hoped Italians would willingly accept them.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] U.S. reformers in the ARC continued to believe in the necessity of American intervention in 'reforming' Italy.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In July 1918 the ARC established a hospital at the entrance of Vladivostok harbor, followed by eight more hospitals during that year.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Vladivostok Refugee hospital was opened in early 1919 in former naval barracks and had up to 250 beds.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The ARC provided drugs and medical supplies to Russian hospitals during the civil war.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] By the time World War II ended in September 1945, American society contributed over $784 million in support of the American Red Cross.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Standards for the female volunteers were higher than those in the military, be a college grad, 25 years of age, steller reference letters, pass physical examinations as well as personality tests in interviews.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] During the start of the war the red cross knew the country was somewhat leaning on them making sure they had the volunteers and staff.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] They made sure to have communications dialed in through the war.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Forecasting a major disaster before the landfall of Hurricane Katrina, ARC enlisted 2,000 volunteers to be on a "stand by" deployment list.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] According to ARC, during and after hurricanes Katrina, Wilma and Rita, they opened 1,470 shelters and registered 3.8 million overnight stays.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] 300,000 American Red Cross workers (82% unpaid) provided sheltering, casework, communication and assessment services throughout these events.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In addition, 346,980 comfort kits (which contain hygiene essentials such as toothpaste, soap, washcloths and toys for children) and 205,360 cleanup kits (containing brooms, mops and bleach) were distributed.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The organization served 68 million snacks and meals.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Disaster Health services provided 596,810 contacts, and Disaster Mental Health services 826,590 contacts.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Emergency financial assistance was provided to 1.4 million families, including 4 million people.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Katrina was the first natural disaster in the United States that ARC utilized their "Safe and Well" family location website.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Following the crash of commuter aircraft Comair Flight 5191, the Bluegrass Area Chapter and ARC Critical Response Team (CRT) members were dispatched.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] This was the worst air disaster in the United States since American Airlines Flight 587.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Family and Friends reception centers were established near the arrival and departure airports and in Cincinnati, site of the Comair headquarters.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Local chapters in Georgia, Alabama, Kentucky and California provided health and mental health services to family and friends not present in Lexington.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Volunteers also staffed the local Emergency Operations Center (EOC) in Lexington, Kentucky.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In response to the Central Florida Tornado of February 2007, ARC began a large scale disaster relief operation.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] 40,000 pre-packaged meals were sent by ARC, and across the nation, almost 400 American Red Cross volunteers were deployed to assist with local relief efforts.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The organization deployed more than 30 Emergency Response Vehicles for community food and supply distribution.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC immediately responded to the May 2007 Tornado Outbreak in central Kansas by setting up emergency shelters for displaced residents and started the distribution of over 39,000 meals, water and relief supplies.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Following the collapse of the I-35W Mississippi River bridge, the Twin Cities Area Chapter responded with their Disaster Action Team to provide food, information and comfort.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] A family service center was set up, and mental health counselors deployed to numerous locations.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Donations contributed for this cause totaled US$138,368 and covered the cost of services but not $65,000 in unexpected expenses.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Weather and the collapse placed 70% of Minnesota counties in federal primary or contiguous disaster areas during that August.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Following the Hawaii wildfires in early August 2023, the ARC began a large-scale disaster relief operation (DRO).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] More than 1,300 volunteers have been deployed since the fires began.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In partnership with the county government, the ARC has been able to provide displaced residents with more than 257,000 overnight emergency shelter and hotel room stays on Maui and Oahu.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The ARC has recruited 15 volunteers from Oklahoma and Kansas regions to go to Florida to help prepare shelters and meal preparations for those affected by the hurricane prior to the hurricane hitting landfall.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Volunteers have set up for upwards to 35,000 overnight stays and 513,000 meals.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC, as part of the International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement and its nearly 100 million volunteers, educates and mobilizes communities to overcome life-threatening vulnerabilities.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC International Services Department focuses on global health, disaster preparedness and response, Restoring Family Links and international humanitarian law dissemination.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC is involved with international projects, including the Measles and Rubella Partnership, the migration and refugee crisis, and the Nepal earthquake.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC international disaster response and preparedness programs provide relief and development assistance to millions of people annually who suffer as a result of natural and human-made disasters.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] To respond quickly and effectively, ARC has pre-positioned emergency relief supplies in three warehouses managed by the International Federation in Dubai, Malaysia, and Panama that are used to respond to disasters.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] An Emergency Response Unit (ERU) is another method with which ARC responds to international emergencies.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] An ERU is made up of trained personnel and pre-packaged equipment that is crucial in responding to sudden, large-scale disasters and emergencies in remote locations.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] American Red Cross ERUs specialize in providing emergency relief supplies and IT and Telecommunications for American Red Cross response operations.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC works with the Red Cross Red Crescent network to aid countries after disasters.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC provides relief after a request from a country in need and then uses trained disaster responders and relief supplies strategically positioned worldwide to respond immediately.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC may also provide financial aid to disaster relief efforts using donations given to the organization.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The Ebola Outbreak in West Africa, Hurricane Dorian in the Bahamas, and Typhoon Haiyan in the Philippines are some of the international disasters that ARC has responded to.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In 1911, the ARC initiated its first international disaster-prevention project in the Huai River Valley.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The ARC hired engineers to redirect the Huai River to prevent the yearly flooding that ruined crops and caused famine.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Jameson, recommended a financial commitment to drainage, flood prevention, and land reclamation which he promised would result in 'the elimination of the suffering, starvation, and degeneration of several millions of people', which would substantially reduce 'unrest and lawlessness'.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The plan's ambition to re-engineer the Chinese landscape was representative of the increasingly global ambitions of the ARC and the new direction the organization was taking prior to World War I.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] On January 12, 2010, a magnitude 7.0 Mw earthquake struck the Haitian coast 10 miles from the capital of Port-au-Prince, causing massive damage, more than 200,000 deaths and displacing nearly 2 million people.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] As of March 2011, ARC announced it had allocated $314 million for Haiti earthquake relief and recovery.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC funded recovery projects to provide transitional homes, health services, disaster preparedness, water and sanitation improvements and livelihoods development.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] It provided funds for school fees for affected families.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] As of June 2011, ARC had raised approximately $484 million for Haiti relief and recovery efforts.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] A series of reports by NPR and ProPublica found that much of the money Americans donated never made it to help people in Haiti and promises to rebuild neighborhoods were never met.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC International Services global health initiatives focus on preventing and combating infectious diseases such as HIV/AIDS and measles on a large scale.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Through cost-effective, community-based health interventions, ARC targets people in need and focuses on accessibility and equity of care, community participation, and integration with other community development initiatives, such as water and sanitation projects and food and nutrition programs.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] An example of ARC International Services health programming is the Measles Initiative, launched in 2001, as a partnership committed to reducing measles deaths globally.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The initiative provides technical and financial support to governments and communities on vaccination campaigns and disease surveillance worldwide.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the United Nations Foundation, UNICEF and the World Health Organization.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The Measles Initiative has supported vaccination campaigns in more than 60 countries, mostly in Africa and Asia.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Since 2001, the initiative has helped vaccinate one billion children in more than 60 developing countries.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The initiative supported the distribution of more than 37 million insecticide-treated mosquito nets for malaria prevention, 81 million doses of de-worming medicine, 95 million doses of polio vaccine, and 186 million doses of vitamin A.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] As of January 1, 2023, the initiative became known as the Measles & Rubella Partnership.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The Measles Initiative had been previously renamed in 2012, when the founding members of the organization decided on the inclusion of rubella elimination to the program, changing the name to the Measles and Rubella Initiative.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The change to the Measles & Rubella Partnership came after the adoption of the Measles and Rubella Strategic Framework 2030.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] With the change, new core partners Gavi and the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation have been added.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In December 2006, ARC became a founding partner of the Malaria No More campaign.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The campaign was formed by leading non-governmental organizations to inspire individuals, institutions, and organizations in the private sector to support a comprehensive approach to end malaria, a devastating but preventable disease.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC supported local Red Cross and Red Crescent volunteers in Africa who educated families and communities about malaria prevention and treatment, such as the proper and consistent use of insecticide-treated bed nets.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC provided technical assistance and capacity-building support to its partners in difficult-to-reach communities.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC handles international tracing requests and searches for families who have been separated.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] This service attempts to re-establish contact between separated family members.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Restoring Family Links services provide the exchange of hand-written Red Cross Messages between individuals and their relatives who may be refugees or prisoners of war.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] At any given time, ARC Restoring Family Links program is handling the aftermath of 20–30 wars and conflicts.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The worldwide structure of Red Cross and Red Crescent National Societies and the International Committee of the Red Cross make this service possible.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] When new information from former Soviet Union archives became available in the 1990s, a special unit was created to handle World War II and Holocaust tracing services.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC International Services educates the American public about the guiding principles of international humanitarian law (IHL) for conduct in warfare as set forth by the Geneva Conventions of 1949.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In doing so, ARC International Services provides support to ARC chapters in their IHL dissemination efforts, offering courses and providing instructor training.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC provides emergency and non-emergency services to the United States military.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The most notable service is emergency family communications, where families can contact the Red Cross to send important family messages (such as a death in the family, or new birth).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The agency operates call centers to provide these services.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC works closely with other military societies, such as the Department of Veterans Affairs, to provide other services to service members and their families.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC is not involved with prisoners of war; these are monitored by the International Committee of the Red Cross, the international body.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] One criticism of American Red Cross services to the military stems from stories about ARC charging troops during the Second World War and Korean War token fees for "comfort items" such as toothpaste, coffee, donuts, and cigarettes and for off-base food and lodging.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The fee suggestion had been made in a letter dated March 1942 from the Secretary of War Henry L.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The suggestion was that Allied soldiers were being charged money so Americans should be charged too so as to "ensure an equitable distribution among all service personnel of American Red Cross resources".
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The American Red Cross adopted the Secretary's suggestion as policy.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] During World War II, ARC operated the American Red Cross Clubmobile Service to provide servicemen with food, entertainment and "a connection home." In a June 18, 1945, address to Congress, General Dwight D.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Another account of an American Red Cross World War II worker is related in letters by Evelyn Merritt Welden, compiled in the book *How to Play During a War: A Free Spirit's Life in Letters*, by her son, Lynne Whelden.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] During the Vietnam War 627 American women served in the **ARC Supplemental Recreation Overseas Program**.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] At the invitation of the United States Army the "Donut Dollies" provided morale-boosting games to soldiers.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Due to the mobility of the UH-1 Iroquois, Vietnam Donut Dollies were able to visit troops in forwarding operating positions.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] The 2008 documentary film *A Touch of Home: The Vietnam War's Red Cross Girls* tells the story of these women.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] ARC also provided services to entertain wounded soldiers at the Great Lakes Naval Hospital during the Vietnam War.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In 2011, the Service to the Armed Forces (SAF) unit was reorganized and began receiving $24 million per year from Congress for operating expenses.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Along with being downsized there was a consolidation into four regional locations (San Diego, California, Ft.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] Sill, Oklahoma, Louisville, Kentucky, and Springfield, Massachusetts).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In 2012 the first stories began breaking about long call times and the poor quality of response from call takers, along with questions about whether money was being used appropriately.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p01] In 2015, the San Diego and Springfield locations were closed because an online option for families was implemented.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] On August 7, 2007, Johnson & Johnson (J&J) filed suit against ARC over its sub licensing of the International Red Cross image for the production of first aid kits and similar products, which it alleged competed with the company's products.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] The suit also asked for the destruction of all non-Johnson & Johnson Red Cross Emblem bearing products and demanded that ARC pay punitive damages and J&J's legal fees.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] The American Red Cross' position was that it had licensed its name to first aid kit makers in an effort to encourage readiness for disasters and that license revenues supported humanitarian work.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] J&J claimed that the American Red Cross's commercial ventures were outside the scope of historically well-agreed usage and were in direct violation of federal statutes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] On May 14, 2008, a federal judge ruled against J&J.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] In June 2008, the two organizations announced a settlement had been reached allowing both parties to use the symbol.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] The FDA took court action against ARC in response to deficiencies in their procedures for ensuring blood supply safety.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] The resulting consent decree outlines violations of federal law that ARC engaged in before 1993.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] The consent decree was amended in 2003 with penalties for specific violations.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] The FDA continued to apply pressure and fines to ARC in order to enforce compliance with regulations, including a $1.7 million fine in June 2008.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] ARC worked closely with the FDA to develop a more robust system.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] The systems resulted in a five-year period of sustained compliance that led to the release from the Consent Decree as of December 4, 2015.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] ARC faced criticism from lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender and queer (LGBTQ+) advocacy organizations for prohibiting men who have sex with men from donating blood.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] This policy was an FDA requirement for all blood collection companies and organizations in the United States.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] Specifically, the FDA instructs blood collection organizations to "defer for 12 months from the most recent sexual contact, a man who has had sex with another man during the past 12 months".
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] Consequently, ARC was legally unable to collect blood from such men.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] In 2006, along with the AABB and America's Blood Centers, ARC petitioned the FDA to remove the requirement from blood donations, citing better screening technologies.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] In August 2020, the American Red Cross reported on its website that its deferral of men who have sex with men from donating blood for three months after any sexual contact with another man is aligned with the newly updated guidance issued by the U.S.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] Then in May 2023, the FDA approved a policy to allow "monogamous gay and bi men to finally donate blood immediately" - however would take some time to fully implement across the whole United States of America.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] An automatic 3-month deferred period still continually applies to non-monogamous individuals, regardless of sexual orientation, who have anal sex.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] In March 2006, investigations of allegations of fraud and theft by volunteers and contractors within ARC Katrina operations were launched by the Louisiana Attorney-General and the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] In response, ARC increased its internal and external education of the organization's fraud and a waste hotline for confidential reporting to a third-party agency.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] The organization also elected to implement a background check policy for all volunteers and staff, starting in 2006.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] In April 2006, an unnamed former ARC official leaked reports made by the International Committee of the Red Cross and the British Red Cross.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] Such reports are typical of a large-scale disaster relief operation involving other national Red Cross societies to solicit their input, but are usually confidential and not released to the general public.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] These particular reports were particularly critical of ARC operations in Katrina-affected regions, although the British Red Cross report strongly praised ARC volunteers for their efforts.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] After the 2010 Haiti earthquake, the Red Cross raised $490 million in relief donations.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] The charts put to the press claim that a substantial amount was spent in the years following, but first-person accounts share another story.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] As of 2015, a total of six homes were built.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] In October 2014, independent public interest news broadcasters NPR and ProPublica published investigative reports on the Red Cross's handling of Hurricanes Sandy and Isaac, citing internal Red Cross documents and interviews with former Red Cross and government officials.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] It criticized the organization's response in failing to meet the immediate needs of victims.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] It also described "an organization so consumed with public relations that it hindered the charity's ability to provide disaster services".
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] Trevor Riggen, a Red Cross vice president, said he was "very proud of the services [the Red Cross] provided".
[src:2013-colorado-floods/american-red-cross-p02] He further stated that the "volume of services and the speed at which [the Red Cross] provided it speaks to the quality of service of the volunteers and staff on the ground".
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The **National Railroad Passenger Corporation**, doing business as **Amtrak** (/ˈæmtræk/; reporting marks **AMTK**, **AMTZ**), is the national passenger railroad company of the United States.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] It operates intercity rail service in every contiguous U.S. state except for Wyoming and South Dakota as well as in three Canadian provinces.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Founded in 1971 as a quasi-public corporation to operate many U.S. passenger rail routes, Amtrak receives a combination of state and federal subsidies but is managed as a for-profit organization.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The company's headquarters is located one block west of Union Station in Washington, D.C.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak is headed by a Board of Directors, two of whom are the secretary of transportation and chief executive officer (CEO) of Amtrak, while the other eight members are nominated to serve a term of five years.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak's network includes over 500 stations along 21,400 miles (34,400 km) of track.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] It directly owns approximately 623 miles (1,003 km) of this track and operates an additional 132 miles (212 km) of track; the remaining mileage is over rail lines owned by other railroad companies.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] While most track speeds are limited to 79 mph (127 km/h) or less, several lines have been upgraded to support top speeds of 110 mph (180 km/h), and parts of the Northeast Corridor support top speeds of 160 mph (260 km/h).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In fiscal year 2025, Amtrak served 34.5 million passengers and had $2.7 billion in adjusted ticket revenue, with more than 22,100 employees.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Nearly 87,000 passengers ride more than 300 Amtrak trains daily.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Nearly two-thirds of passengers come from the 10 largest metropolitan areas and 83% of passengers travel on routes shorter than 400 miles (645 km).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In 1916, 98% of all commercial intercity travelers in the United States moved by rail, and the remaining 2% moved by inland waterways.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Nearly 42 million passengers used railways as primary transportation.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Passenger trains were owned and operated by the same privately owned companies that operated freight trains.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] As the 20th century progressed, patronage declined in the face of competition from buses, air travel, and the car.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] New streamlined diesel-powered trains, such as the *Pioneer Zephyr*, were popular with the traveling public but could not reverse the trend.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] By 1940, railroads held 67 percent of commercial passenger-miles in the United States.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In real terms, passenger-miles had fallen by 40% since 1916, from 42 billion to 25 billion.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Traffic surged during World War II, aided by troop movement and gasoline rationing.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The railroad's market share surged to 74% in 1945, with a massive 94 billion passenger-miles.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] After the war, railroads rejuvenated their overworked and neglected passenger fleets with fast and luxurious streamliners.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] These new trains brought only temporary relief to the overall decline.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Even as postwar travel exploded, passenger travel percentages of the overall market share fell to 46% by 1950, and then 32% by 1957.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The railroads had lost money on passenger service since the Great Depression, but deficits reached $723 million in 1957.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] For many railroads, these losses threatened financial viability.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The causes of this decline were heavily debated.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The National Highway System and airports, both funded by the government, competed directly with the railroads, which, unlike the airline, bus, and trucking companies, paid for their own infrastructure.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] American car culture was also on the rise in the post–World War II years.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Progressive Era rate regulation limited the railroads' ability to turn a profit.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Railroads also faced antiquated work rules and inflexible relationships with trade unions.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] To take one example, workers continued to receive a day's pay for 100-to-150-mile (160 to 240 km) workdays.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Matters approached a crisis in the 1960s.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Passenger service route-miles fell from 107,000 miles (172,000 km) in 1958 to 49,000 miles (79,000 km) in 1970, the last full year of private operation.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The diversion of most United States Post Office Department mail from passenger trains to trucks, airplanes, and freight trains in late 1967 deprived those trains of badly needed revenue.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In direct response, the Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway filed to discontinue 33 of its remaining 39 trains, ending almost all passenger service on one of the largest railroads in the country.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The equipment the railroads had ordered after World War II was now 20 years old, worn out, and in need of replacement.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] As passenger service declined, various proposals were brought forward to rescue it.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The 1961 Doyle Report proposed that the private railroads pool their services into a single body.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Similar proposals were made in 1965 and 1968 but failed to attract support.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The federal government passed the High Speed Ground Transportation Act of 1965 to fund pilot programs in the Northeast Corridor, but this did nothing to address passenger deficits.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In late 1969, multiple proposals emerged in the United States Congress, including equipment subsidies, route subsidies, and, lastly, a "quasi-public corporation" to take over the operation of intercity passenger trains.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Matters were brought to a head on June 21, 1970, when the Penn Central, the largest railroad in the Northeastern United States and teetering on bankruptcy, filed to discontinue 34 of its passenger trains.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In October 1970, Congress passed, and President Richard Nixon signed into law (against the objections of most of his advisors), the **Rail Passenger Service Act**.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Proponents of the bill, led by the National Association of Railroad Passengers (NARP), sought government funding to ensure the continuation of passenger trains.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Of the 26 railroads still offering intercity passenger service in 1970, only six declined to join the NRPC.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Nearly everyone involved expected the experiment to be short-lived.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The Nixon administration and many Washington insiders viewed the NRPC as a politically expedient way for the President and Congress to give passenger trains a "last hurrah" as demanded by the public.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] They expected the NRPC to quietly disappear as public interest waned.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] After *Fortune* magazine exposed the manufactured mismanagement in 1974, Louis W.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Menk, chairman of the Burlington Northern Railroad, remarked that the story was undermining the scheme to dismantle Amtrak.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Proponents also hoped that government intervention would be brief and that Amtrak would soon be able to support itself.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Neither view had proved to be correct; popular support allowed Amtrak to continue in operation longer than critics imagined, while financial results made passenger train service returning to private railroad operations infeasible.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The Rail Passenger Service Act gave the Secretary of Transportation, at that time John A.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Volpe, thirty days to produce an initial draft of the endpoints of the routes the NRPC would be required by law to serve for four years.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] On November 24 Volpe presented his initial draft consisting of 27 routes to Nixon, which he believed would make a $24-million profit by 1975.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The Office of Management and Budget believed Volpe and the DOT's analysis was far too optimistic, with director George Shultz arguing to cut the number of routes by around half.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Nixon agreed with Shultz, and the public draft presented by Volpe on November 30 consisted of only 16 routes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The initial reaction to this heavily-cut-back proposed system from the public, the press, and congressmen was strongly negative.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] It made front-page headlines across the country and it was quickly leaked that the DOT had wanted a far larger system than the White House would approve.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The ICC produced its own report on December 29, criticising the proposed draft and arguing for the inclusion of 15 additional routes, giving further ammunition to the congressmen who wanted an expanded system.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Further wrangling between the DOT and the White House produced the final list of routes on January 28, 1971, adding 5 additional routes to the November 30 draft.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] These required routes had only their endpoints specified; the selection of the actual routes to be taken between the endpoints was left to the NRPC, which had just three months to decide them before it was due to start service.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Consultants from McKinsey & Company were hired to perform this task, and their results were publicly announced on March 22.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] At the same time, the NRPC had hired Lippincott & Margulies to create a brand for it and replace its original working brand name of Railpax.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] On March 30, L&M's work was presented to the NRPC's board of incorporators, who unanimously agreed on the "headless arrow" logo and on the new brand name "Amtrak", a portmanteau of the words *America* and *trak*, the latter itself a sensational spelling of *track*.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The name change was publicly announced less than two weeks before operations began.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak received no rail tracks or rights-of-way at its inception.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] All of Amtrak's routes were continuations of prior service, although Amtrak pruned about half the passenger rail network.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Of the 366 train routes that operated previously, Amtrak continued only 184.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Several major corridors became freight-only, including the ex-New York Central Railroad's Water Level Route from New York to Ohio and Grand Trunk Western Railroad's Chicago to Detroit route.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The reduced passenger-train schedules created confusion amongst staff.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] At some stations, Amtrak service was available only late at night or early in the morning, prompting complaints from passengers.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Disputes with freight railroads over track usage caused some services to be rerouted, temporarily cancelled, or replaced with buses.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] On the other hand, the creation of the Los Angeles–Seattle *Coast Starlight* from three formerly separate train routes was an immediate success, resulting in an increase to daily service by 1973.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Needing to operate only half the train routes that had operated previously, Amtrak would lease around 1,200 of the best passenger cars from the 3,000 that the private railroads owned.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] All were air-conditioned, and 90% were easy-to-maintain stainless steel.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] When Amtrak took over, passenger cars and locomotives initially retained the paint schemes and logos of their former owners which resulted in Amtrak's running trains with mismatched colors – the "Rainbow Era".
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In mid-1971, Amtrak began purchasing some of the equipment it had leased, including 286 EMD E and F unit diesel locomotives, 30 GG1 electric locomotives and 1,290 passenger cars.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] By 1975, the official Amtrak color scheme was painted on most Amtrak equipment and newly purchased locomotives and the rolling stock began appearing.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak inherited problems with train stations (most notably deferred maintenance) and redundant facilities from the competing railroads that once served the same communities.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Chicago is a prime example; on the day prior to Amtrak's inception, intercity passenger trains used five different Chicago terminals: LaSalle, Dearborn, North Western Station, Central, and Union.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The trains at LaSalle remained there, as their operator Rock Island could not afford to opt into Amtrak.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Of all the trains serving Dearborn Station, Amtrak retained only a pair of Santa Fe trains, which relocated to Union Station beginning with the first Amtrak departures on May 1, 1971.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Dearborn Station closed after the last pre-Amtrak trains on the Santa Fe arrived in Chicago on May 2.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] None of the intercity trains that had served North Western Station became part of the Amtrak system, and that terminal became commuter-only after May 1.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The trains serving Central Station continued to use that station until an alternate routing was adopted in March 1972.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In New York City, Amtrak had to maintain two stations (Penn and Grand Central) due to the lack of track connections to bring trains from upstate New York into Penn Station; a problem that was rectified once the Empire Connection was built in 1991.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The Amtrak Standard Stations Program was launched in 1978 and proposed to build a standardized station design across the system with an aim to reduce costs, speed construction, and improve its corporate image.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] However, the cash-strapped railroad would ultimately build relatively few of these standard stations.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak soon had the opportunity to acquire rights-of-way.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Following the bankruptcy of several northeastern railroads in the early 1970s, including Penn Central, which owned and operated the Northeast Corridor (NEC), Congress passed the Railroad Revitalization and Regulatory Reform Act of 1976.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] A large part of the legislation was directed to the creation of Conrail, but the law also enabled the transfer of the portions of the NEC not already owned by state authorities to Amtrak.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak acquired the majority of the NEC on April 1, 1976.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] (The portion in Massachusetts is owned by the Commonwealth and managed by Amtrak.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The route from New Haven to New Rochelle is owned by New York's Metropolitan Transportation Authority and the Connecticut Department of Transportation as the New Haven Line.) This mainline became Amtrak's "jewel" asset, and helped the railroad generate revenue.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] While the NEC ridership and revenues were higher than those of any other segment of the system, the cost of operating and maintaining the corridor proved to be overwhelming.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] As a result, Amtrak's federal subsidy was increased dramatically.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In subsequent years, other short-route segments not needed for freight operations were transferred to Amtrak.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In its first decade, Amtrak fell far short of financial independence, a shortage that continues today, but it did find modest success rebuilding trade.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Outside factors discouraged competing transport, such as fuel shortages which increased costs of automobile and airline travel, and strikes which disrupted airline operations.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Investments in Amtrak's track, equipment and information also made Amtrak more relevant to America's transportation needs.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak's ridership increased from 16.6 million in 1972 to 21 million in 1981.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In February 1978, Amtrak moved its headquarters to 400 North Capitol Street NW, Washington, D.C.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In 1982, former Secretary of the Navy and retired Southern Railway head William Graham Claytor Jr. came out of retirement to lead Amtrak.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] During his time at Southern, Claytor was a vocal critic of Amtrak's prior managers, who all came from non-railroading backgrounds.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Transportation Secretary Drew Lewis cited this criticism as a reason that the Democrat Claytor was acceptable to the Reagan White House.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Despite frequent clashes with the Reagan administration over funding, Claytor enjoyed a good relationship with Lewis, John H.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Riley, the head of the Federal Railroad Administration (FRA), and with members of Congress.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Limited funding led Claytor to use short-term debt to fund operations.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Building on mechanical developments in the 1970s, high-speed Washington–New York Metroliner Service was improved with new equipment and faster schedules.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Travel time between New York and Washington, D.C., was reduced to under 3 hours due to system improvements and limited stop service.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] This improvement was cited as a reason that Amtrak grew its share of intercity trips between the cities along the corridor.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Elsewhere in the country, demand for passenger rail service resulted in the creation of five new state-supported routes in California, Illinois, Missouri, Oregon and Pennsylvania, for a total of 15 state-supported routes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak added two trains in 1983, the *California Zephyr* between Oakland and Chicago via Denver and revived the *Auto Train*, a unique service that carries both passengers and their vehicles.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak advertised it as a great way to avoid traffic along the I-95 running between Lorton, Virginia, (near Washington, D.C.) and Sanford, Florida, (near Orlando) on the Silver Star alignment.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In 1980s and 1990s, stations in Baltimore, Chicago, and Washington, D.C., received major rehabilitation and the Empire Connection tunnel opened in 1991, allowing Amtrak to consolidate all New York services at Penn Station.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Despite the improvements, Amtrak's ridership stagnated at roughly 20 million passengers per year, amid uncertain government aid from 1981 to about 2000.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In the early 1990s, Amtrak tested several different high-speed trains from Europe on the Northeast Corridor.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] An X 2000 train was leased from Sweden for test runs from October 1992 to January 1993, followed by revenue service between Washington, D.C., and New York City from February to May and August to September 1993.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Siemens showed the ICE 1 train from Germany, organizing the ICE Train North America Tour which started to operate on the Northeast Corridor on July 3, 1993.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In 1993, Thomas Downs succeeded Claytor as Amtrak's fifth president.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The stated goal remained "operational self-sufficiency".
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] By this time, however, Amtrak had a large overhang of debt from years of underfunding.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In the mid-1990s, Amtrak suffered through a serious cash crunch.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Under Downs, Congress included a provision in the Taxpayer Relief Act of 1997 that resulted in Amtrak's receiving a $2.3 billion tax refund that resolved their cash crisis.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] However, Congress also instituted a "glide path" to financial self-sufficiency, excluding railroad retirement tax act payments.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] George Warrington became the sixth president in 1998, with a mandate to make Amtrak financially self-sufficient.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Under Warrington, the company tried to expand into express freight shipping, placing Amtrak in competition with the "host" freight railroads and the trucking industry.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] On March 9, 1999, Amtrak unveiled its plan for the *Acela Express,* a high-speed train on the Northeast Corridor between Washington, D.C., and Boston.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Several changes were made to the corridor to make it suitable for higher-speed electric trains.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The Northend Electrification Project extended existing electrification from New Haven, Connecticut, to Boston to complete the overhead power supply along the 454-mile (731 km) route, and several grade crossings were improved or removed.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Ridership increased during the first decade of the 21st century after the implementation of capital improvements in the NEC and rises in automobile fuel costs.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The inauguration of the high-speed *Acela* in late 2000 generated considerable publicity and led to major ridership gains.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] However, through the late 1990s and very early 21st century, Amtrak could not add sufficient express freight revenue or cut sufficient other expenditures to break even.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] By 2002, it was clear that Amtrak could not achieve self-sufficiency, but Congress continued to authorize funding and released Amtrak from the requirement.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Gunn replaced Warrington as seventh president.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In a departure from his predecessors' promises to make Amtrak self-sufficient in the short term, Gunn argued that no form of passenger transportation in the United States is self-sufficient as the economy is currently structured.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Highways, airports, and air traffic control *all* require large government expenditures to build and operate, coming from the Highway Trust Fund and Aviation Trust Fund paid for by user fees, highway fuel and road taxes, and, in the case of the General Fund, from general taxation.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Gunn dropped most freight express business and worked to eliminate deferred maintenance.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] A plan by the Bush administration "to privatize parts of the national passenger rail system and spin off other parts to partial state ownership" provoked disagreement within Amtrak's board of directors.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Gunn's replacement, Alexander Kummant (2006–08), was committed to operating a national rail network, and like Gunn, opposed the notion of putting the Northeast Corridor under separate ownership.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] He said that shedding the system's long-distance routes would amount to selling national assets that are on par with national parks, and that Amtrak's abandonment of these routes would be irreversible.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In late 2006, Amtrak unsuccessfully sought annual congressional funding of $1 billion for ten years.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In early 2007, Amtrak employed 20,000 people in 46 states and served 25 million passengers a year, its highest number since its founding in 1970.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] *Politico* noted a key problem: "the rail system chronically operates in the red.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] A pattern has emerged: Congress overrides cutbacks demanded by the White House and appropriates enough funds to keep Amtrak from plunging into insolvency.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Boardman replaced Kummant as president and CEO in late 2008.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] From May 2011 to May 2012, Amtrak celebrated its 40th anniversary with festivities across the country that started on National Train Day (May 7, 2011).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] A commemorative book entitled *Amtrak: An American Story* was published, a documentary was created, six locomotives were painted in Amtrak's four prior paint schemes, and an Exhibit Train toured the country visiting 45 communities and welcoming more than 85,000 visitors.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] After years of almost revolving-door CEOs at Amtrak, in December 2013, Boardman was named "Railroader of the Year" by *Railway Age* magazine, which noted that with over five years in the job, he is the second-longest serving head of Amtrak since it was formed more than 40 years ago.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] On December 9, 2015, Boardman announced in a letter to employees that he would be leaving Amtrak in September 2016.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] He had advised the Amtrak Board of Directors of his decision the previous week.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] On August 19, 2016, the Amtrak Board of Directors named former Norfolk Southern Railway President & CEO Charles "Wick" Moorman as Boardman's successor with an effective date of September 1, 2016.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] During his term, Moorman took no salary and said that he saw his role as one of a "transitional CEO" who would reorganize Amtrak before turning it over to new leadership.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] On November 17, 2016, the Gateway Program Development Corporation (GDC) was formed for the purpose of overseeing and effectuating the rail infrastructure improvements known as the Gateway Program.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] GDC is a partnership of the States of New York and New Jersey and Amtrak.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The Gateway Program includes the Hudson Tunnel Project, to build a new tunnel under the Hudson River and rehabilitate the existing century-old tunnel, and the Portal North Bridge, to replace a century-old moveable bridge with a modern structure that is less prone to failure.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Later projects of the Gateway Program, including the expansion of track and platforms at Penn Station New York, construction of the Bergen Loop and other improvements will roughly double capacity for Amtrak and NJ Transit trains in the busiest, most complex section of the Northeast Corridor.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In June 2017, former Delta and Northwest Airlines CEO Richard Anderson was announced as Amtrak's next President & CEO.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Anderson began the job on July 12, assuming the title of President immediately and serving alongside Moorman as "co-CEOs" until the end of the year.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Three years later, on April 15, 2020, Atlas Air Chairman, President and CEO William Flynn was named Amtrak President and CEO.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In addition to Atlas Air, Flynn held senior roles at CSX Transportation, SeaLand Services and GeoLogistics Corp.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Anderson would remain with Amtrak as a senior advisor until December 2020.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] As Amtrak approached profitability in 2020, the company undertook planning to expand and create new intermediate-distance corridors across the country.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Included were several new services in Ohio, Tennessee, Colorado, and Minnesota, among other states.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] During the COVID-19 pandemic, Amtrak continued operating as an essential service.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] It started requiring face coverings the week of May 17, and limited sales to 50% of capacity.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Most long-distance routes were reduced to three weekly round trips in October 2020.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In March 2021, following President Joe Biden's American Jobs Plan announcement, Amtrak CEO Bill Flynn outlined a proposal called Amtrak Connects US that would expand state-supported intercity corridors with an infusion of upfront capital assistance.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] This would expand service to cities including Las Vegas, Phoenix, Baton Rouge, Nashville, Chattanooga, Louisville, Columbus (Ohio), Wilmington (North Carolina), Cheyenne, Montgomery, Concord, and Scranton.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Also in March 2021, Amtrak announced plans to return 12 of its long-distance routes to daily schedules later in the spring.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Most of these routes were restored to daily service in late-May 2021.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] However, a resurgence of the virus caused by the Omicron variant caused Amtrak to modify and/or suspend many of these routes again from January to March 2022.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Stephen Gardner, a former Amtrak intern and longtime executive, became the company's CEO in January 2022.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] He resigned abruptly on March 19, 2025, amid reports that the Trump administration had pressured him to step down.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Earlier that month, Trump advisor Elon Musk had expressed an intention to privatize Amtrak.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak is required by law to operate a national route system.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak has presence in 46 of the 48 contiguous states, as well as the District of Columbia (with only thruway connecting services in Wyoming and no services in South Dakota).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak services fall into three groups: inter-city services on the Northeast Corridor, state-supported inter-city services outside the Northeast Corridor, and medium- and long-distance services (known within Amtrak as the National Network).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak receives federal funding for the vast majority of its operations including the central spine of the Northeast Corridor as well as for its National Network routes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In addition to the federally funded routes, Amtrak partners with transportation agencies in 18 states to operate other inter-city and medium-distance routes outside of the Northeast Corridor, some of which connect to it or extend beyond it.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In addition to its inter-city services, Amtrak also operates commuter services under contract for three public agencies: the MARC Penn Line in Maryland, Shore Line East in Connecticut, and Metrolink in Southern California.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Service on the Northeast Corridor (NEC), between Boston, and Washington, D.C., as well as between Philadelphia and Harrisburg, is powered by overhead lines; for the rest of the system, diesel-electric locomotives are used.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Routes vary widely in the frequency of service, from three-days-a-week trains on the *Sunset Limited* and the Cardinal, to several times per hour on the Northeast Corridor.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] For areas not served by trains, Amtrak Thruway routes provide guaranteed connections to trains via buses, vans, ferries and other modes.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The most popular and heavily used services are those running on the Northeast Corridor (NEC), including the *Acela* and *Northeast Regional*.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The NEC runs between Boston and Washington, D.C. via New York City and Philadelphia.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The NEC services accounted for 4.4 million of Amtrak's 12.2 million passengers in fiscal year 2021.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Outside the NEC the most popular services are located in California, including the *Pacific Surfliner*, *Capitol Corridor*, and *Gold Runner*, which are supplemented by an extensive network of connecting buses.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Together, the California corridor trains accounted for a combined 2.35 million passengers in fiscal year 2021.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Four of the six busiest stations by boardings are on the NEC: New York Penn Station (first), Washington Union Station (second), Philadelphia 30th Street Station (third), and Boston South Station (fifth).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The other two are Chicago Union Station (fourth) and Los Angeles Union Station (sixth).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] On-time performance is calculated differently for airlines than for Amtrak.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] A plane is considered on-time if it arrives within 15 minutes of the schedule.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak uses a sliding scale, with trips under 250 miles (400 km) considered late if they are more than 10 minutes behind schedule, up to 30 minutes for trips over 551 miles (887 km) in length.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Outside the Northeast Corridor and stretches of track in Southern California and Michigan, most Amtrak trains run on tracks owned and operated by privately owned freight railroads.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] BNSF is the largest host to Amtrak routes, with 6.3 million train-miles.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Freight rail operators are required under federal law to give dispatching preference to Amtrak trains.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak has accused freight railroads of violating or skirting these regulations, resulting in passenger trains having to wait for freight traffic to clear the track.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The railroads' dispatching practices were investigated in 2008, resulting in stricter laws about train priority.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Subsequently, Amtrak's overall on-time performance went up from 74.7% in fiscal 2008 to 84.7% in 2009, with long-distance trains and others outside the NEC seeing the greatest benefit.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The *Missouri River Runner* jumped from 11% to 95%, becoming one of Amtrak's best performers.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The *Texas Eagle* went from 22.4% to 96.7%, and the *California Zephyr*, with a 5% on-time record in 2008, went up to 78.3%.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] This improved performance coincided with a general economic downturn, resulting in the lowest freight-rail traffic volumes since at least 1988, meaning less freight traffic to impede passenger traffic.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In 2018, Amtrak began issuing "report cards" to host railroads, grading each based on the railroad's impact to on-time performance.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The first report card, issued in March 2018, includes one A (given to Canadian Pacific) and two Fs (given to Canadian National and Norfolk Southern).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak's 2020 host report card gives Canadian Pacific and Canadian National an A, BNSF and CSX a B, Union Pacific a C+, and Norfolk Southern a D−.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak's 2023 host report card gives Canadian Pacific Kansas City an A, CSX and Canadian National a B+, BNSF a B, Norfolk Southern a B−, and Union Pacific a C−.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak's median on-time performance between 2018 and 2023 was 74.5%, reaching a high of 80% in 2020.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] It was highest on the Northeast Corridor (81.3%).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The vast majority of hours of delay, about 57.5% on average, were caused by the host railroad.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Long-distance routes performed similarly to the total weighted on-time percentage.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak carried 15.8 million passengers in 1972, its first full year of operation.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Ridership has increased steadily ever since, carrying a record 32 million passengers in fiscal year (FY) 2019, more than double the total in 1972.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] For the fiscal year ending on September 30, 2020, Amtrak reported 16.8 million passengers, with the decline resulting from effects of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] FY 2021 saw ridership decrease more, with 12.2 million passengers reported.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] FY 2022 saw an increase to 22.9 million passengers, further increasing to 28.6 million passengers in FY 2023.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In FY 2024, Amtrak's ridership increased to 32.8 million passengers, surpassing the record set in FY 2019.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] FY 2025 saw ridership continue to increase to 34.5 million passengers, setting an all-time record for the second year in a row.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak's loyalty program, Guest Rewards, is similar to the frequent-flyer programs of many airlines.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Guest Rewards members accumulate points by riding Amtrak and through other activities, and can redeem these points for free Amtrak tickets and other rewards.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak offers the USA Rail Pass, valid for 10 segments (rides) in 30 days; and the California rail pass which is valid for 7 days of travel in a period of 21 days.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Along the NEC and in several other areas, Amtrak owns 730 miles (1,170 km) of track, including 17 tunnels comprising 29.7 miles (47.8 km) of track and 1,186 bridges comprising 42.5 miles (68.4 km) of track.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In several places, primarily in New England, Amtrak leases tracks, providing track maintenance and controlling train movements.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Most often, these tracks are leased from state, regional, or local governments.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The lines are further divided into services.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In addition to these lines, Amtrak owns station and yard tracks in Chicago, Los Angeles, New Orleans, New York City, Oakland, Orlando, Portland, Oregon, Seattle, Philadelphia, and Washington, D.C.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak leases station and yard tracks in Hialeah, near Miami, Florida, from the State of Florida.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak owns New York Penn Station, Chicago Union Station, Philadelphia 30th Street Station, Baltimore Penn Station and Providence Station.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Through the Washington Terminal Company, in which it owns a 99.7 percent interest, it owns the rail infrastructure around Washington Union Station.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] It also holds a 99% interest in 30th Street Limited, a partnership responsible for redeveloping the area in and around Philadelphia's 30th Street Station.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak also owns Passenger Railroad Insurance.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak organizes its business into six "service lines", which are treated like divisions at most companies.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] As of July 2023, 117 of 385 stations were in compliance with the Americans with Disabilities Act.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak operates a fleet of 2,142 railway cars and 425 locomotives for revenue service and railroad operations, collectively referred to as its rolling stock.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Notable examples include the GE Genesis and Siemens Charger diesel locomotives, the Siemens ACS-64 electric locomotive, the Amfleet and Viewliner series of single-level passenger cars, the Superliner series of double-decker passenger cars, and 20 Acela Express high-speed trainsets.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In addition, Amtrak operates 196 locomotives and railcars that are wholly owned by its state partners.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The railroad is currently undertaking a fleet replacement effort, spending $2.4 billion on 28 *NextGen Acela* (Avelia Liberty) trainsets for its flagship *Acela* service and $7.3 billion for 65 Airo trainsets for other Northeast Corridor services.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Separately, California and a consortium of Midwestern states have purchased Siemens Venture trainsets for use on Amtrak-operated routes within their regions; these began entering service in 2022.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In 2023, Amtrak issued a request for proposals to replace hundreds of bilevel railcars used on long-distance routes, and a similar proposal for single-level long-distance railcars was issued in 2025.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak first offered free Wi-Fi service to passengers aboard the *Downeaster* in 2008, the *Acela* and the *Northeast Regional* trains on the NEC in 2010, and the *Amtrak Cascades* in 2011.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In February 2014, Amtrak rolled out Wi-Fi on corridor trains out of Chicago.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] When all the Midwest cars offer the AmtrakConnect service, about 85% of all Amtrak passengers nationwide will have Wi-Fi access.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] As of 2014, most Amtrak passengers have access to free Wi-Fi.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The service has developed a reputation for being unreliable and slow due to its cellular network connection; on some routes it is usually unusable, either freezing on the login page or, if it manages to log in, failing to provide any internet bandwidth.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak launched an e-ticketing system on the *Downeaster* in November 2011 and rolled it out nationwide on July 30, 2012.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak allows carry-on baggage on all routes; services with baggage cars allow checked baggage at selected stations.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] With the passage of the Wicker Amendment in 2010, passengers are allowed to put lawfully owned, unloaded firearms in checked Amtrak baggage, reversing a decade-long ban on such carriage.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The Amtrak Express cargo service used to provide small-package and less-than-truckload shipping between most Amtrak stations that handle checked baggage (over 100 cities).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Cargo traveled alongside checked luggage in baggage cars.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] However, the service was suspended in 2020.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] As of July 2025, there have been no plans to resume service.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Amtrak is popular among bicycle touring enthusiasts due to the ease of riding with a bike.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In contrast to airlines, which require riders to dismantle their bicycles and place them in specialized bags, most Amtrak trains have onboard bike racks in either the coaches or checked baggage car.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Bicycle reservations are required on most routes and cost up to $20.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] On most routes, Amtrak provides a Cafe where passengers can purchase food and drinks.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] On long-distance trains, passengers in sleeper accommodations are provided complimentary meals.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Passengers on the Cardinal, City of New Orleans, Crescent, Lake Shore Limited, and the Texas Eagle from Chicago to San Antonio have Flex Dining, which features microwaved meals.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Passengers on all other routes like the California Zephyr and Sunset Limited have Traditional Dining, which features chef-cooked meals.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] As of 2023, the average Amtrak employee annual salary was $121,000 per year.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Most Amtrak workers are legally classified as "railroad employees" and thus make contributions to the federal Railroad Retirement system.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Some critics, such as the National Association of Railroad Passengers, argue that Amtrak is thereby "subsidizing" freight railroad pensions by as much as US$150 million/year.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In recent times, efforts at reforming passenger rail have addressed labor issues.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] In 1997 Congress released Amtrak from a prohibition on hiring contractors outside the corporation (and outside its unions); since that time, many of Amtrak's employees have been working without a contract.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] The most recent contract, signed in 1999, was mainly retroactive.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Because of the fragmentation of railroad unions, Amtrak workers are represented by 14 separate trade unions, with as many as 24 simultaneous contracts between them as of 2009, a situation which has made contract negotiations more difficult.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p01] Former Amtrak president Alexander Kummant followed a cooperative posture with Amtrak's unions, ruling out plans to privatize large parts of the company's workforce.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Per passenger mile, Amtrak is 30–40 percent more energy-efficient than commercial airlines and automobiles overall, though the exact figures for particular routes depend on load factor along with other variables.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] As of 2023, 1% of rail in the United States is electrified.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] On select areas of Amtrak's Northeast Corridor, where some locomotives are electrified, Amtrak emits up to 70-80% less greenhouse gas emissions than personal vehicle and flight travel.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] In 2005, Amtrak's carbon dioxide equivalent emissions per passenger were 0.411 lbs/mi (0.116 kg per km).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] This amount is similar to that of a car with two people, about twice as high as the UK rail average (where more of the system is electrified), about four times the average US motorcoach, and about eight times a Finnish electric intercity train or fully loaded fifty-seat coach.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] It is, however, about two thirds of the raw CO2-equivalent emissions of a long-distance domestic flight.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] In 2018, specifically in northeastern US, Amtrak's carbon dioxide equivalent emissions per passenger were 0.280 lbs/mi for diesel locomotives and 0.134 lbs/mi for electric locomotives.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] The average emissions for the combined ratio of Amtrak diesel and electric routes is 0.227 lbs/mi.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Per route, passenger rail travel covers and average of 30% more miles than air travel due to the nature of its course and path.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Rail creates less carbon dioxide emissions than flying for trips up to and beyond 1,100 miles, but its CO2 advantage fade on longer routes past 500 miles.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Diesel trains cause additional regional air pollution, impacting the ecosystems around the sites of operation.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] More stops along train routes can lead to higher greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Delays in operation can lead to excess locomotive idling, also leading to higher greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Amtrak rail facilities located in Delaware were cited as the state's largest source of polychlorinated biphenyl (PCB) contamination into the Delaware River, which build up in the tissue of animals and are human carcinogens.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] In 2020, Amtrak announced a goal to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions 40 percent below 2010 levels by 2030.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Amtrak has also set a target of achieving net-zero emissions by 2045.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] To achieve this target, Amtrak plans to source 100 percent of its electricity from renewable energy by the year 2035.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] As of 2023, Amtrak obtains 61% of its electricity from carbon-free sources and is making gains towards its sustainability goals.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] To further advance its emissions targets, Amtrak has implemented a range of sustainability measures.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] These measures include reducing excessive diesel locomotive idling, acquiring more fuel-efficient electric and diesel locomotives, procuring cleaner energy for electric operations, and opting for more environmentally friendly lighting in passenger railcars and stations.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Amtrak also requires all new management hires to complete sustainability and emissions training courses.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Amtrak railways and surrounding infrastructure are susceptible to degradation by natural causes over time.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Railways experience water damage from climate-change backed increases in rainfall in wet areas, and rail buckling caused by hotter and dryer seasons in naturally dry areas.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] In September 2021, the remnants of Hurricane Ida flooded the Amtrak Northeast Corridor running from Boston to Washington, D.C., and caused it to shut down for an entire day.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] In February 2023, heavy snowfall and debris on tracks caused major disruptions from delays to cancellations.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Amtrak receives annual appropriations from federal and state governments to supplement operating and capital programs.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Amtrak commenced operations in 1971 with $40 million in direct federal aid, $100 million in federally insured loans, and a somewhat larger private contribution.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Officials expected that Amtrak would break even by 1974, but those expectations proved unrealistic and annual direct federal aid reached a 17-year high in 1981 of $1.25 billion.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] During the Reagan administration, appropriations were halved and by 1986, federal support fell to a decade low of $601 million, almost none of which were capital appropriations.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] In the late 1980s and early 1990s, Congress continued the reductionist trend even while Amtrak expenses held steady or rose.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Amtrak was forced to borrow to meet short-term operating needs, and by 1995 Amtrak was on the brink of a cash crisis and was unable to continue to service its debts.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] In response, in 1997 Congress authorized $5.2 billion for Amtrak over the next five years – largely to complete the *Acela* capital project – on the condition that Amtrak submit to the ultimatum of self-sufficiency by 2003 or liquidation.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] While Amtrak made financial improvements during this period, it did not achieve self-sufficiency.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] In 2004, a stalemate in federal support of Amtrak forced cutbacks in services and routes as well as the resumption of deferred maintenance.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] In fiscal 2004 and 2005, Congress appropriated about $1.2 billion for Amtrak, $300 million more than President George W.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] However, the company's board requested $1.8 billion through fiscal 2006, the majority of which (about $1.3 billion) would be used to bring infrastructure, rolling stock, and motive power back to a state of good repair.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] In Congressional testimony, the DOT Inspector General confirmed that Amtrak would need at least $1.4 billion to $1.5 billion in fiscal 2006 and $2 billion in fiscal 2007 just to maintain the status quo.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] In 2006, Amtrak received just under $1.4 billion, with the condition that Amtrak would reduce (but not eliminate) food and sleeper service losses.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Thus, dining service was simplified and now requires two fewer on-board service workers.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Only *Auto Train* and *Empire Builder* services continue regular made-on-board meal service.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] In 2010 the Senate approved a bill to provide $1.96 billion to Amtrak, but cut the approval for high-speed rail to a $1 billion appropriation.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] State governments have partially filled the breach left by reductions in federal aid.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] With the dramatic rise in gasoline prices during 2007–08, Amtrak saw record ridership.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Capping a steady five-year increase in ridership overall, regional lines saw 12% year-over-year growth in May 2008.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] 294, the Passenger Rail Improvement and Investment Act of 2007 (70–22), sponsored by Senators Frank Lautenberg and Trent Lott.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Despite a veto threat by President Bush, a similar bill passed the House on June 11, 2008, with a veto-proof margin (311–104).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] The final bill, spurred on by the September 12 Metrolink collision in California and retitled Passenger Rail Investment and Improvement Act of 2008, was signed into law by President Bush on October 16, 2008.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] The bill appropriates $2.6 billion a year in Amtrak funding through 2013.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Amtrak points out that in 2010, its farebox recovery (percentage of operating costs covered by revenues generated by passenger fares) was 79%, the highest reported for any U.S. passenger railroad.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] In 2019, which was Amtrak's best year in farebox recovery, Amtrak was short by only $29.4 million from breaking even for that year.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Amtrak has argued that it needs to increase capital program costs in 2013 in order to replace old train equipment because the multi-year maintenance costs for those trains exceed what it would cost to simply buy new equipment that would not need to be repaired for several years.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] However, despite an initial request for more than $2.1 billion in funding for the year, the company had to deal with a year-over-year cut in 2013 federal appropriations, dropping to under $1.4 billion for the first time in several years.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Amtrak's budget is allocated on only a yearly basis, and it has been argued by Joseph Vranich that this makes multi-year development programs and long-term fiscal planning difficult if not impossible.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Congress granted Amtrak $563 million for operating and $922 million for capital programs.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Amtrak received $22 billion in advance appropriations and $19 billion in fully authorized funds.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Government aid to Amtrak was controversial from the beginning.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] The formation of Amtrak in 1971 was criticized as a bailout serving corporate rail interests and union railroaders, not the traveling public.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Critics have asserted that Amtrak has proven incapable of operating as a business and that it does not provide valuable transportation services meriting public support, making it a "mobile money-burning machine".
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Many fiscal conservatives have argued that subsidies should be ended, national rail service terminated, and the NEC turned over to private interests.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Critics also question Amtrak's energy efficiency, though the U.S.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Department of Energy considers Amtrak among the most energy-efficient forms of transportation.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] The Rail Passenger Service Act of 1970, which established Amtrak, specifically states that, "The Corporation will not be an agency or establishment of the United States Government".
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Then common stock was issued in 1971 to railroads that contributed capital and equipment; these shares convey almost no benefits, but their holders declined a 2002 buy-out offer by Amtrak.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] There are currently 109.4 million shares of preferred stock, at a par value of $100 per share, all held by the US government.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] As of February 2015, there were 9.4 million shares of common stock, with a par value of $10 per share, held by American Premier Underwriters (53%), BNSF (35%), Canadian Pacific (7%) and Canadian National (5%).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] In addition to the United States Secretary of Transportation and its CEO, Amtrak's Board of Directors has eight presidentially-nominated and senate-confirmed seats.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] Presidentially appointed members serve nominally five-year terms but are allowed to serve until their successor is confirmed, and no more than five of the eight may belong to one political party.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] At least one of these eight must be an individual with a disability.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] The Secretary may be represented at Board meetings by their designee.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/amtrak-p02] After settling for $17 million in the 2017 Washington state train crash, to prevent further lawsuits, the board adopted a new policy requiring arbitration.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] On August 25, 1855, the Kansas Territorial Legislature created a huge Arapahoe County to govern the entire western portion of the Territory of Kansas.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] The county was named for the Arapaho Nation, who lived in the region.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] In July 1858, gold was discovered along the South Platte River in Arapahoe County (in present-day Englewood).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] This discovery precipitated the Pike's Peak Gold Rush.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Many residents of the mining region felt disconnected from the remote territorial governments of Kansas and Nebraska, so they voted to form their own Territory of Jefferson on October 24, 1859.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] The following month, the Jefferson Territorial Legislature organized 12 counties for the new territory, including a smaller Arapahoe County.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Denver City served as the county seat of Arapahoe County.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] The Jefferson Territory never received federal sanction, and when the State of Kansas was admitted to the Union on January 29, 1861, the mining regions temporarily reverted to unorganized territory.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] On February 28, 1861, Congress passed an act organizing the Territory of Colorado, using present-day borders.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] On November 1, 1861, the Colorado Territorial Assembly organized the 17 original counties of Colorado, including a new Arapahoe County.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Arapahoe County originally stretched from the line of present-day Sheridan Boulevard 160 miles (260 km) east to the Kansas border, and from the line of present-day County Line Road 30 miles (48 km) north to the 40th parallel north (168th Avenue).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Denver City served as the county seat of Arapahoe County until 1902.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] In 1901, the Colorado General Assembly voted to split Arapahoe County into three parts — a new consolidated City and County of Denver, a new Adams County, and the remainder of the Arapahoe County to be renamed South Arapahoe County.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] A ruling by the Colorado Supreme Court, subsequent legislation, and a referendum delayed the reorganization until November 15, 1902.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Governor James Bradley Orman designated Littleton as the temporary county seat of South Arapahoe County.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] On April 11, 1903, the Colorado General Assembly changed the name of South Arapahoe County back to Arapahoe County.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] On November 8, 1904, Arapahoe County voters chose Littleton over Englewood by a vote of 1310 to 829 to be the permanent county seat.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Census Bureau, the county has a total area of 805 square miles (2,080 km2), of which 798 square miles (2,070 km2) are land and 7.3 square miles (19 km2) (0.9%) are covered by water.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] The county measures 72 mi (116 km) east-west and 4 to 12 mi (6.4 to 19.3 km) north-south.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Two exclaves of Arapahoe County are entirely surrounded by the City and County of Denver, the City of Glendale, and the Holly Hills neighborhood, a census-designated place.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] As of the 2020 census, the county had a population of 655,070.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Of the residents, 23.4% were under the age of 18 and 13.8% were 65 years of age or older; the median age was 36.6 years.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] For every 100 females there were 98.6 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 96.6 males.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] 97.9% of residents lived in urban areas and 2.1% lived in rural areas.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] The racial makeup of the county was 60.5% White, 10.8% Black or African American, 1.0% American Indian and Alaska Native, 6.5% Asian, 0.3% Native Hawaiian and Pacific Islander, 8.3% from some other race, and 12.6% from two or more races.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Hispanic or Latino residents of any race comprised 20.7% of the population.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] There were 250,206 households in the county, of which 32.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them and 26.0% had a female householder with no spouse or partner present.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] About 26.4% of all households were made up of individuals and 9.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] There were 262,493 housing units, of which 4.7% were vacant.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Among occupied housing units, 62.5% were owner-occupied and 37.5% were renter-occupied.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] The homeowner vacancy rate was 0.9% and the rental vacancy rate was 7.3%.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] As of the census of 2000, 487,967 people, 190,909 households, and 125,809 families were residing in the county.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] The population density was 608 people/mi2 (235 people/km2).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] The 196,835 housing units averaged 245 per square mile (95/km2).
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] The racial makeup of the county was 79.93% White, 7.67% African American, 0.66% Native American, 3.95% Asian, 0.12% Pacific Islander, 4.51% from other races, and 3.16% from two or more races.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Hispanics or Latinos of any race made up 11.81% of the population.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Of the 190,909 households, 34.90% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 51.20% were married couples living together, 10.60% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.10% were not families.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] About 27.00% of all households were made up of individuals, and 5.90% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] The average household size was 2.53, and the average family size was 3.11.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] For every 100 females, there were 97.10 males.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 94.20 males.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] The median income for a household was $53,570, and for a family was $63,875.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Males had a median income of $41,601 versus $31,612 for females.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] The per capita income for the county was $28,147.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] About 4.20% of families and 5.80% of the population were below the poverty line, including 7.00% of those under age 18 and 5.10% of those age 65 or over.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Arapahoe County is home to nine public school districts: Aurora, Bennett, Byers, Cherry Creek, Deer Trail, Englewood, Littleton, Sheridan, and Strasburg.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] There are also several private schools throughout the county, including St.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Mary's Academy in Cherry Hills Village, Regis Jesuit High School in Aurora, and Kent Denver School in Englewood.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Arapahoe County is home to two large community colleges: Arapahoe Community College in Littleton, and the Community College of Aurora.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] The county is also home to the University of Colorado Anschutz Medical Campus and the Denver South campus of Colorado Technical University, both located in Aurora.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Arapahoe County was once a classic bastion of suburban conservatism.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] In the 1924 Colorado gubernatorial election, Republican Clarence Morley, who was openly affiliated with the Ku Klux Klan, won over 66% of the vote in Arapahoe County, a higher percentage than he received in any other county in Colorado.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] In addition, the county for many years was represented in congress by Republican Tom Tancredo, a hardcore conservative known for his controversial anti-immigration, anti-Catholic, and nativist political beliefs.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] As the Denver Metro Area grew in the 1960s and beyond, Arapahoe County became the most Republican county in the state outside of Colorado Springs.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] However, heavy urbanization, demographic changes and population increases - such as the rapid diversification of Aurora's population and younger professionals in the southern suburbs - have caused the county to become much more competitive since the 1990s.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] It swung from a 22-point win for George H.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Bush in 1988 to only a three-point win in 1992.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] By the turn of the millennium, it had become more of a suburban swing county.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] In 2008, the county swung over dramatically to support Barack Obama, who became the first Democrat to carry it since 1964, and only the second since 1936.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] It swung from a four-point win for George W.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] Bush in 2004 to a 13-point win for Obama in 2008.
[src:2013-colorado-floods/arapahoe-county-colorado] In the 2020 election, Joe Biden turned in the strongest showing for a Democrat in over a century, becoming the first Democrat to win over 60% of the vote since 1916.
